00:04:18.680 --> 00:04:22.720
[Unknown]: Salman welcome to the scene in the unseen. Thank you so much. I mean, thank you for having me

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:28.040
[Amit Varma]: Salman I really enjoyed reading your book the great disappointment which did not live up to his title in the sense

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:30.040
[Amit Varma]: It wasn't a great disappointment for me

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:36.760
[Amit Varma]: Before we kind of get to the book tell me a little bit about you know your career as an economist and

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:41.360
[Guest]: all the journeys you made so far. Well, you know, I went for higher studies to the US and

00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:48.160
[Guest]: You know realized that I enjoyed policy work and didn't really want to get into the PhD stream

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:50.400
[Guest]: You know going to academics and all that

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:56.840
[Guest]: So the World Bank was always one of those things that my father used to tell me about you talk about the World Bank

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:00.920
[Guest]: The IMF and GATT those days we had the GATT not the WTO

00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:06.040
[Guest]: So he always thought of me as an international civil servant and you know, I pursued that

00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:09.440
[Guest]: And somehow landed up at the World Bank

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:15.480
[Guest]: Passed around my resume quite a bit and then you know started doing in fact

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:20.480
[Guest]: my first assignment at the World Bank was about evaluation and the importance of results in

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:23.160
[Guest]: in development work and

00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:28.280
[Guest]: After all these years now I feel that there's a lot more emphasis on

00:05:28.840 --> 00:05:34.920
[Guest]: What the outcomes and impacts of programs are as opposed to just the inputs because we used to focus so much on inputs earlier

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:40.120
[Guest]: So in the World Bank, I've you know done a lot of different work. I worked on

00:05:40.680 --> 00:05:45.600
[Guest]: Strategic issues I worked on actually I worked on natural disasters

00:05:45.960 --> 00:05:52.400
[Guest]: And how to manage their impacts and I've actually led teams in Europe and Central Asia

00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:56.440
[Guest]: I worked on you know forming international partnerships

00:05:57.320 --> 00:06:02.480
[Guest]: so a lot of different stuff, but then you know eventually when I moved to India in

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:08.720
[Guest]: 2011 I quit the World Bank because I thought that you know, there are plenty of people with my kind of

00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:15.080
[Guest]: Background in the US and I wanted to kind of do more work in Kashmir and in and in India

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:20.080
[Guest]: I thought this international exposure to policy work would probably help there

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:25.360
[Guest]: So, you know I took you know, in some ways I kind of took that kind of

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:33.360
[Guest]: Lens and went moved to India and of course the reality on the ground is very different from what you see from Washington

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:37.440
[Guest]: So it was very very very interesting experience, but I actually started delving more into

00:06:37.960 --> 00:06:44.360
[Guest]: India's political economy, which I found to be very interesting. And of course India's challenges are you know immense?

00:06:44.360 --> 00:06:47.080
[Guest]: And so, you know, I think I think that's how I can just

00:06:47.080 --> 00:06:49.560
[Guest]: Meandered around and ultimately ended up

00:06:50.440 --> 00:06:57.360
[Guest]: Working on India writing about the Indian economy and eventually writing this book and now you're part of the Congress and you're one of the

00:06:57.840 --> 00:07:02.040
[Amit Varma]: spokespeople and you know one thing that sort of I wonder is you know

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:07.080
[Amit Varma]: Harry Truman once spoke about how he would like 100 economists because economists keep saying well on the one hand this and

00:07:07.720 --> 00:07:12.760
[Amit Varma]: And you know, so as an economist, obviously you're trained to look at every side of an issue to

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:18.440
[Amit Varma]: Examine all the nuances and so on but in politics, especially I would imagine if you're the spokesman of a party

00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:21.240
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes you have to stick to a simple narrative

00:07:21.240 --> 00:07:25.920
[Amit Varma]: You can't do on the one hand this on the other hand that how do you reconcile those different challenges?

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:31.080
[Amit Varma]: Well, yeah, I think that is a significant challenge for people

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:34.440
[Guest]: Especially who come with you know with my background

00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:38.200
[Guest]: But you know, I mean first I come from

00:07:38.200 --> 00:07:44.880
[Guest]: You know a family where politics was already kind of ingrained in us. My father has been a politician for decades

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:50.920
[Guest]: He was a member of Parliament for many many terms and also minister. So I think I've seen it up close

00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:55.720
[Guest]: but when you join a political party, which I did in

00:07:56.560 --> 00:08:02.680
[Guest]: 2013 or so formally and then you're asked to represent the party and its views

00:08:02.680 --> 00:08:07.000
[Guest]: Of course, you do get kind of taken in by the political party

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.200
[Guest]: you can just take it into this one way kind of

00:08:11.520 --> 00:08:13.800
[Guest]: communication so to speak but I think

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:19.160
[Guest]: the way I dealt with this was basically stick to facts as much as possible and

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.360
[Guest]: If so, I can have focused on data

00:08:23.240 --> 00:08:29.680
[Guest]: so my big thing was I'll try and use data to make my argument and I remember in the

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.880
[Guest]: 2014 in the run-up to the 2014 election I

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:37.920
[Guest]: I used to you know face a barrage of questions on the economy on inflation

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:43.280
[Guest]: Fiscal deficits and this thing and that thing and what I would rely on is, you know

00:08:43.600 --> 00:08:48.680
[Guest]: UPA's growth story its poverty reduction story and of course they have a problem as well

00:08:48.680 --> 00:08:56.120
[Guest]: But you know in development you have problems and it there's no there is no kind of clean development model. It's pretty you know

00:08:56.800 --> 00:08:59.320
[Guest]: You have to roll up your sleeves. You have to go

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:06.680
[Guest]: Knee-deep into mud and it's you know, sometimes you have progress sometimes you regress, but that's what economic development is

00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:09.240
[Guest]: so I think I kept that as my kind of

00:09:10.840 --> 00:09:15.120
[Guest]: Compass so to speak so I would not just spew the party line

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:21.000
[Guest]: I would actually try to kind of back my assertions with data. So in that sense I created a space for myself

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:25.960
[Guest]: Which I thought was available and and that's how I did it

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:32.000
[Guest]: It's not easy, of course, because you know, you know and and writing this book actually, you know

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:35.280
[Guest]: It's not been that simple because I didn't want this to become

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:41.600
[Guest]: Oh, there's a Congress guy and he's written a book about Modi and against Modi. So I didn't want it to be like that

00:09:41.600 --> 00:09:44.840
[Guest]: I've tried my best actually to be as objective as possible

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:49.400
[Guest]: I've given the government credit wherever I could but for the most part, you know

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:55.180
[Guest]: I really feel the title reflects what I see about this government even though you disagree

00:09:55.180 --> 00:09:59.120
[Guest]: In fact others have told me that they don't agree with the title but for different reasons

00:09:59.120 --> 00:09:59.720
[Amit Varma]: No, no

00:09:59.720 --> 00:10:04.200
[Amit Varma]: when I I was actually kidding what I meant was that reading the book was not a disappointment for me as

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:08.080
[Amit Varma]: Far as Modi's term is I think calling it a disappointment is an understatement

00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:15.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and and I think you're absolutely right in the sense that one of the things that surprised me when I was reading the

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:19.000
[Amit Varma]: book is that there are moments when you're critical of the UPA especially

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:25.480
[Amit Varma]: UPA too and there are moments where you give credit where credit is due to Modi and and we'll come to all of that but

00:10:25.480 --> 00:10:30.840
[Amit Varma]: Before we sort of come to the five-year period of 2014 to 2019 which the book is about

00:10:31.480 --> 00:10:33.480
[Amit Varma]: I'd like you to also

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:36.040
[Amit Varma]: Set a sort of context for me

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:43.860
[Amit Varma]: In terms of what has happened in the Indian economy before that and if I can ask you one broad question that sitting in 2014

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:51.440
[Amit Varma]: What are the broad lessons that policymakers could have taken from all those decades of governance of independence India before that?

00:10:52.300 --> 00:10:57.700
[Guest]: Well, you know the context for the book is you know to my mind the context for the book is twofold

00:10:58.460 --> 00:11:00.300
[Guest]: one is

00:11:00.300 --> 00:11:06.140
[Guest]: You know on a lighter note and that is the commissioning agent at penguin had been after my life for two years

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:08.860
[Guest]: She'd seen my articles and newspapers and all that

00:11:08.860 --> 00:11:12.340
[Guest]: She felt that I could write something and initially we thought we'd write about Kashmir

00:11:12.340 --> 00:11:16.060
[Guest]: then I said no, I know the economy reasonably well and

00:11:16.820 --> 00:11:19.380
[Guest]: Ultimately, you know and with the elections approaching

00:11:19.380 --> 00:11:24.300
[Guest]: She said wouldn't you want to do an assessment of how the government is done? And it was a compelling argument

00:11:24.300 --> 00:11:28.620
[Guest]: And I said, okay. Yeah, that makes sense to me. I've done a three-year, you know

00:11:29.100 --> 00:11:32.660
[Guest]: Modinomics at three earlier and then I said, okay, maybe I can just build on that

00:11:33.300 --> 00:11:39.780
[Guest]: But the more important context for this book is and then I'll get to the lessons what I think that were missed

00:11:39.780 --> 00:11:46.180
[Guest]: Was this this slogan this kind of a statement by candidate Modi that he would do in 60

00:11:46.740 --> 00:11:48.740
[Guest]: Months what others have not done in 60 years

00:11:49.300 --> 00:11:52.500
[Guest]: That really stuck with me, you know because I was in the middle of the campaign

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:59.620
[Guest]: I would go on TV all the time and that particular statement was it really kind of drew people in but I knew

00:11:59.660 --> 00:12:04.860
[Guest]: From an economic development perspective how unfair it was to all those who had come before him

00:12:04.860 --> 00:12:09.740
[Guest]: So I think that is how I say I can if that gave me the kind of passion to write

00:12:09.740 --> 00:12:13.460
[Guest]: I think for me that was the most important thing. In fact in this book

00:12:13.460 --> 00:12:18.100
[Guest]: I constantly talk about that and I wanted to see that's why I wrote inheritance

00:12:18.340 --> 00:12:24.460
[Guest]: The first part of this book is about inheritance. What did different prime ministers receive as inheritance?

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:26.940
[Guest]: I talked about Nehru and the six million refugees

00:12:27.100 --> 00:12:32.340
[Guest]: Which was the biggest refugee crisis outside of World War two and also a lack of food

00:12:32.340 --> 00:12:37.580
[Guest]: I mean those were the big challenges Nehru faced and then I kind of list what other prime ministers

00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:44.300
[Guest]: Faced and all that and then so in some sense that is the context. I mean being unfair to predecessors

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:50.900
[Guest]: Belittling India's achievements and then trying to say that you would do something that I knew to be impossible

00:12:51.140 --> 00:12:53.700
[Guest]: but you know, I think if you

00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:56.460
[Guest]: If you ask most people in India

00:12:56.460 --> 00:13:02.540
[Guest]: They'll say the demonetization and GST were the big big issues that come to mind from an economic management perspective

00:13:03.140 --> 00:13:08.500
[Guest]: From my perspective it is more about the banking sector. I think that is the big, you know

00:13:08.980 --> 00:13:10.900
[Guest]: lesson that they missed and

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:15.860
[Guest]: That is banking sector problems do not resolve themselves easily, right?

00:13:15.860 --> 00:13:17.860
[Guest]: I mean and I think it was a budding

00:13:18.340 --> 00:13:25.340
[Guest]: Banking sector crisis it was still I think much smaller than it is now at that time

00:13:25.340 --> 00:13:29.980
[Guest]: There's plenty of evidence from around the world that these crises need to be tackled

00:13:30.540 --> 00:13:34.140
[Guest]: sooner because you know, the banking sector is the lifeblood of the economy and

00:13:35.940 --> 00:13:41.340
[Guest]: International institutions like the World Bank ADB IMF and and by the way the government's own

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:44.580
[Guest]: Department of Economic Affairs it all be there RBI

00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:50.260
[Guest]: Everybody had been flagging this that this is a problem and I somehow feel that this was not addressed

00:13:50.260 --> 00:13:56.060
[Guest]: Promptly and I think that may be one of the big reasons why the economy has not

00:13:56.940 --> 00:14:02.580
[Guest]: Done as well and mind you demonetize the economy was slowing down before demonetization

00:14:03.340 --> 00:14:09.380
[Guest]: For several quarters before demonetization happened. So I think the part of the reason is because

00:14:09.940 --> 00:14:13.460
[Guest]: The system was clogged up. Well, you know corporate balance sheets are also kind of

00:14:13.460 --> 00:14:19.060
[Guest]: Stressed so I think that was one lesson the other lesson. I mean, obviously, you know, I don't know

00:14:19.620 --> 00:14:23.140
[Guest]: There's so many lessons from international development from India's own experience

00:14:23.980 --> 00:14:25.980
[Guest]: We'd had joblessness for a long time

00:14:26.340 --> 00:14:31.420
[Guest]: We had high growth but still we were not creating the kinds of decent jobs that we need our young people to

00:14:31.940 --> 00:14:35.060
[Guest]: Take on I don't think there was sufficient focus on that

00:14:35.060 --> 00:14:39.540
[Guest]: It was almost like you can just manufacture your way out of it without trying to understand

00:14:39.540 --> 00:14:45.140
[Guest]: that the world had moved on and yet in some ways the industrialized for some time and

00:14:46.180 --> 00:14:53.180
[Guest]: I'm not sure why we were not focusing on issues like education and I think this government also missed that opportunity

00:14:53.180 --> 00:14:56.940
[Guest]: You know, why not education? Why not health? Why not?

00:14:57.580 --> 00:15:01.020
[Guest]: malnutrition such Bharat is very important but

00:15:01.620 --> 00:15:06.100
[Guest]: Malnutrition is what gives you productive citizenry for the future. So

00:15:06.100 --> 00:15:09.300
[Guest]: When you have such a mandate when you have I don't know

00:15:09.300 --> 00:15:14.780
[Guest]: But it's almost a wealth of experience and we're still not doing the things that we need to do. I you know, I'm

00:15:15.300 --> 00:15:20.020
[Guest]: Frankly puzzled so I don't know why I think the kind of you know in my question the kind of

00:15:20.340 --> 00:15:25.620
[Amit Varma]: Lessons I was referring to were not not the specifics which we'll come to when we talk about the period the five-year period

00:15:26.100 --> 00:15:30.980
[Amit Varma]: Modi's term but more about broader lessons. For example much as Modi

00:15:30.980 --> 00:15:36.420
[Amit Varma]: Criticized Nehru and in fact blames him for everything. He seems to have the same command and control

00:15:37.140 --> 00:15:43.300
[Amit Varma]: Approach to the economy, which is perhaps not always apt as you point out and you know, you've written in your book about

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:49.060
[Amit Varma]: You know in your section on Indira Gandhi you cite Bhagwati and Panagariya and about how

00:15:49.620 --> 00:15:54.420
[Amit Varma]: The state's dominance over economic affairs cost India in those years 65 to 75

00:15:54.900 --> 00:15:57.860
[Amit Varma]: When India's per capita grew by 0.3 percent

00:15:57.860 --> 00:16:03.700
[Amit Varma]: Per annum GDP growth during that period averaged 2.6 percent and and eventually

00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:07.700
[Amit Varma]: You know that mindset was thrust aside and you know

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:13.460
[Amit Varma]: There were some reforms in the 80s and then more in 91 obviously forced by demon forced by liberalization

00:16:13.460 --> 00:16:18.820
[Amit Varma]: Sorry, so my broader question was that in terms of mindset in in Modi's rhetoric

00:16:18.820 --> 00:16:22.020
[Amit Varma]: It seemed that he had made a lot of those shifts like you pointed out

00:16:22.020 --> 00:16:26.820
[Amit Varma]: He branded himself as a sort of a Thatcherite conservative and he was a bit of a

00:16:26.820 --> 00:16:32.580
[Amit Varma]: Thatcherite conservative and whatever but in his actions, none of those really manifested, you know

00:16:32.580 --> 00:16:36.980
[Amit Varma]: He had the same command and control mindset. He had the same top-down view and

00:16:37.860 --> 00:16:40.180
[Amit Varma]: You know the importance of the state and economic affairs

00:16:40.820 --> 00:16:44.660
[Amit Varma]: In those sense, what are the lessons that you would have liked to have seen?

00:16:45.300 --> 00:16:50.200
[Amit Varma]: What are the lessons that other policymakers had learned but Modi hadn't learned or internalized?

00:16:51.140 --> 00:16:54.420
[Guest]: I think it's not about learning lessons, you know in the sense that you know

00:16:54.420 --> 00:16:58.900
[Guest]: We know that there are lessons that are people who will learn them others who are just not uh, you know

00:16:59.220 --> 00:17:04.820
[Guest]: Prone to learning those kinds of things at all. And I think Modi's, you know, Modi was never a

00:17:05.360 --> 00:17:11.060
[Guest]: Decentralizer in Gujarat, right? I mean Modi's uh, Modi was a strongman in Gujarat. That's how he did things

00:17:11.140 --> 00:17:15.860
[Guest]: He was this decisive. So, you know been so so-called decisive leader who's going to basically

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:22.020
[Guest]: will everything into shape and uh, he managed lots of ministries and that's how he thought

00:17:22.020 --> 00:17:28.340
[Guest]: He would manage India. And in fact, I talked about the centralizing instinct. Uh, you know, uh, I think in

00:17:29.060 --> 00:17:33.620
[Guest]: Maybe the third part of the book where Panagariya basically talks about how you know

00:17:33.860 --> 00:17:35.860
[Guest]: Modi did this and that and he was really

00:17:36.180 --> 00:17:40.260
[Guest]: Focused on getting projects moving and all that whereas I was thinking that you know

00:17:40.260 --> 00:17:43.780
[Guest]: He was centralizing things because that's what he knew. That's who he was

00:17:44.340 --> 00:17:47.780
[Guest]: So it wasn't it's not as if he was suddenly going to change

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:52.900
[Guest]: I personally believe that once you're beyond 30, you're not going to change your core habits

00:17:53.460 --> 00:18:00.260
[Guest]: So, uh, so I don't really think anybody should expect that he would somehow decentralize power

00:18:00.820 --> 00:18:05.400
[Guest]: And I think the lesson for us as citizens and also as observers

00:18:06.100 --> 00:18:07.140
[Guest]: is that

00:18:07.140 --> 00:18:07.540
[Guest]: You know

00:18:07.540 --> 00:18:12.340
[Guest]: It really a lot depends on who's running the government in a country like India where?

00:18:12.340 --> 00:18:18.180
[Guest]: We have a parliamentary democracy at the same time. We we look to someone to lead us and here we have someone who

00:18:18.740 --> 00:18:25.380
[Guest]: Does not believe in the kind of decentralization that India needs because India is too vast too diverse too complicated

00:18:25.860 --> 00:18:30.100
[Guest]: For any central force to run, you know, in fact, you know

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:33.300
[Guest]: My other research which I did not kind of incorporate in the book

00:18:33.940 --> 00:18:38.100
[Guest]: Was about the role of states, you know, we we talk a lot about the center

00:18:38.100 --> 00:18:43.460
[Guest]: We don't talk enough about the states. It's easy to say that the congress party or what did you guys do for 60 years?

00:18:44.020 --> 00:18:46.180
[Guest]: Or meanwhile for the last 30 40 years

00:18:46.740 --> 00:18:51.140
[Guest]: The congress has not been present in big states like Bihar and uh and up

00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:57.300
[Guest]: Where bjp has been present in fits and starts in these kinds of states and in Madhya Pradesh and all this so

00:18:58.100 --> 00:19:01.700
[Guest]: A lot of India's progress is about states. It's about districts

00:19:01.700 --> 00:19:05.460
[Guest]: It's about the village level and I think that's where prime minister

00:19:05.460 --> 00:19:12.500
[Guest]: Rajiv Gandhi had the correct instinct and that was decentralized because that's what so you need somebody at the top

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:14.900
[Guest]: Who'll say you know what if India has to really?

00:19:15.860 --> 00:19:20.180
[Guest]: Progress the one good way to do that would be devolving more power

00:19:20.740 --> 00:19:23.300
[Guest]: To other parts and I don't think so

00:19:24.260 --> 00:19:26.260
[Guest]: even though lessons

00:19:26.500 --> 00:19:31.700
[Guest]: Existed that you need to kind of have broad-based growth. You need to you know

00:19:31.700 --> 00:19:38.180
[Guest]: Need to you know, decentralize you need local level kind of people to take up their development issues

00:19:38.820 --> 00:19:43.220
[Guest]: but those lessons could not have been learned by Modi because had he learned them he would have

00:19:44.100 --> 00:19:47.140
[Guest]: You know, he would have paid attention to them in Gujarat as well

00:19:47.700 --> 00:19:53.940
[Guest]: But that's not who he is. So to expect him to learn those lessons, I think is uh, you know

00:19:54.420 --> 00:19:58.580
[Guest]: To my mind would not be correct. We should just basically say that

00:19:58.580 --> 00:20:04.660
[Guest]: Today it's Modi tomorrow. It could be somebody else. That's somebody else and the kind of power you wield

00:20:05.220 --> 00:20:08.420
[Guest]: May have something to do with what how India progresses in the future

00:20:08.740 --> 00:20:15.220
[Guest]: Mind you that is that maybe one of the reasons coalitions are you have proven to be not the disaster

00:20:15.300 --> 00:20:17.540
[Guest]: That the BJP portrays them to be

00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:23.220
[Guest]: Maybe coalitions are better because you have a lot of give and take you don't have a central authority and you're just going to say

00:20:23.220 --> 00:20:27.380
[Guest]: Okay, everybody gets a piece of the pie and maybe that is how India can develop

00:20:27.380 --> 00:20:32.980
[Guest]: But having a strong central character, I don't think it works. I don't think it has worked

00:20:32.980 --> 00:20:37.540
[Guest]: I think it has worked to the detriment of the country in the last five years and every time there's a

00:20:38.100 --> 00:20:42.580
[Guest]: I fear that every time there's a centralizing force India does not stand to gain

00:20:42.580 --> 00:20:46.180
[Amit Varma]: I agree with you and you know at a time where institutions are being weakened

00:20:46.180 --> 00:20:52.420
[Amit Varma]: I think another advantage of a coalition government is that you have more checks and balances by default in the political economy

00:20:52.420 --> 00:21:00.420
[Amit Varma]: Where other institutions which are supposed to perform that role may not quite be able to before we get started on the book in the Modi years

00:21:00.420 --> 00:21:02.420
[Amit Varma]: A final question about

00:21:02.820 --> 00:21:09.380
[Amit Varma]: UPA 1 and UPA 2 now what mistakes do you think the congress made which will cause their huge defeat in

00:21:10.180 --> 00:21:15.140
[Amit Varma]: 2014 and obviously this period of time the 10 years before that are not a monolithic period

00:21:15.140 --> 00:21:18.100
[Amit Varma]: There were periods of growth. There were periods of very good economic management

00:21:18.100 --> 00:21:20.100
[Amit Varma]: There were periods of very bad economic management

00:21:20.100 --> 00:21:25.220
[Amit Varma]: There were periods of very bad economic management such as when Pranam Mukherjee was finance minister, for example

00:21:25.220 --> 00:21:27.780
[Amit Varma]: And you know that reflected in all the data

00:21:28.100 --> 00:21:28.820
[Amit Varma]: So, you know

00:21:28.820 --> 00:21:34.820
[Amit Varma]: What do you think was like in a sense a failure of at some level and you acknowledge this in the book as well

00:21:34.900 --> 00:21:36.900
[Amit Varma]: They didn't do as well as they should have and that

00:21:37.360 --> 00:21:42.500
[Amit Varma]: Enabled Modi to sweep to power in 2014. Can you can you kind of sum that up for me?

00:21:43.140 --> 00:21:45.140
[Guest]: You know, I think of Modi's rise

00:21:45.140 --> 00:21:51.460
[Guest]: And this amazing victory that the BJP had in 2014. It was like this perfect storm

00:21:51.780 --> 00:21:56.820
[Guest]: The economy was losing steam and I can i've talked about how that happened

00:21:57.620 --> 00:21:59.060
[Guest]: on the other hand

00:21:59.060 --> 00:22:01.780
[Guest]: You had these corruption scandals, you know, some of them were

00:22:02.580 --> 00:22:05.220
[Guest]: Clearly scandals others were not as clear

00:22:05.700 --> 00:22:12.820
[Guest]: Then you had vast kind of organized carder based party that was becoming an alternative and on the other hand you had

00:22:12.820 --> 00:22:14.820
[Guest]: You know this pent-up

00:22:15.220 --> 00:22:16.580
[Guest]: demand from

00:22:16.580 --> 00:22:20.980
[Guest]: Young people for jobs and a better life because they could see on their smartphones what other people around the world had

00:22:21.460 --> 00:22:23.460
[Guest]: And finally you had the messenger

00:22:23.620 --> 00:22:29.700
[Guest]: And was a very unique messenger and had been built up over the years as a kind of a messiah

00:22:29.940 --> 00:22:32.660
[Guest]: So this is a perfect storm of all these things coming together

00:22:33.220 --> 00:22:38.180
[Guest]: That I think delivered this victory. It wasn't any one thing as far as the UPS time is concerned

00:22:38.260 --> 00:22:41.780
[Guest]: Of course, you're right. I mean there was there were periods of high growth and

00:22:41.780 --> 00:22:44.040
[Guest]: and good development poverty reduction

00:22:44.820 --> 00:22:46.260
[Guest]: but I think

00:22:46.260 --> 00:22:47.700
[Guest]: to my mind

00:22:47.700 --> 00:22:54.340
[Guest]: When we look at the 2008 crisis and the response to that, of course the response to that was a pretty big fiscal stimulus

00:22:54.820 --> 00:22:58.740
[Guest]: At that time by the way, not as I record in the book not as big as uh,

00:22:59.140 --> 00:23:05.460
[Guest]: What the us did and what china did but of course, we we did not face the same severity of the crisis as they did

00:23:06.100 --> 00:23:10.420
[Guest]: But I think we were not able to handle that because that that really you know

00:23:10.420 --> 00:23:11.540
[Guest]: uh

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:17.460
[Guest]: If you remember in the aftermath of the global financial crisis india continued growing

00:23:18.500 --> 00:23:24.820
[Guest]: And then it kind of you know, I think it was a sugar high in some ways and was hard to sustain sugar highs, right?

00:23:25.380 --> 00:23:26.580
[Guest]: so, uh

00:23:26.580 --> 00:23:30.980
[Guest]: So I think that was a problem. Of course that uh, you know, there was inflationary issues

00:23:31.380 --> 00:23:35.220
[Guest]: fiscal deficit and you know, unfortunately the way we manage fiscal deficits in the country and

00:23:35.220 --> 00:23:43.220
[Guest]: I think this was true in our times too and more I think so even in this government's time

00:23:43.540 --> 00:23:45.540
[Guest]: You know, you'll sell you'll basically

00:23:46.340 --> 00:23:48.340
[Guest]: You know, you'll take one

00:23:48.660 --> 00:23:50.100
[Guest]: government-owned

00:23:50.100 --> 00:23:52.100
[Guest]: entity and then

00:23:52.260 --> 00:23:55.380
[Guest]: Take up a position in some other government take up the government stake in

00:23:55.940 --> 00:23:59.380
[Guest]: Some other entity and then you say we balance the books and you know

00:23:59.380 --> 00:24:02.340
[Guest]: I think those kinds of things ultimately hurt hurt india

00:24:02.340 --> 00:24:06.820
[Guest]: Or hurt an economy. The other issue is that even we did not

00:24:07.460 --> 00:24:09.300
[Guest]: focus on

00:24:09.300 --> 00:24:11.300
[Guest]: You know, what would sustain?

00:24:11.780 --> 00:24:13.140
[Guest]: progress

00:24:13.140 --> 00:24:17.780
[Guest]: And to my mind, you know and here amartya sen has been talking about it all the time

00:24:18.260 --> 00:24:20.340
[Guest]: And I know he gets a lot of good parts

00:24:20.820 --> 00:24:22.820
[Guest]: uh from the right

00:24:23.220 --> 00:24:26.980
[Guest]: But you know unless we invest in human capital human development

00:24:26.980 --> 00:24:31.940
[Guest]: There is no chance for india to succeed in today's world. There's absolutely no chance

00:24:32.260 --> 00:24:37.860
[Guest]: Uh, so if you do not invest in health if you do not invest in education the right way if you do not actually

00:24:38.260 --> 00:24:40.260
[Guest]: Spend the money properly. I have this

00:24:40.820 --> 00:24:46.580
[Guest]: anecdote in the book about a village called bandi paeen in baramulla where I worked uh,

00:24:47.140 --> 00:24:51.860
[Guest]: For two years before the 2014 election and bandi paeen has eight government schools

00:24:51.860 --> 00:24:58.420
[Guest]: It's a one kilometer long half kilometer wide at its widest village with eight government schools

00:24:58.980 --> 00:25:03.700
[Guest]: One high school three middle schools four primary schools. I don't know what the current situation is at that time

00:25:03.700 --> 00:25:06.340
[Guest]: That was the situation. None of the schools had adequate

00:25:06.980 --> 00:25:10.740
[Guest]: teachers or students or there's no furniture

00:25:11.780 --> 00:25:13.060
[Guest]: so

00:25:13.060 --> 00:25:14.340
[Guest]: We should have had one school

00:25:14.340 --> 00:25:18.260
[Guest]: Maybe even that may not have been viable for that village. You could kind of create a model

00:25:18.340 --> 00:25:20.340
[Guest]: You could kind of consolidate you could bring in

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:25.380
[Guest]: You know teachers to uh work in one place. So teachers there would be enough teachers

00:25:25.380 --> 00:25:28.020
[Guest]: There'd be enough students, but that's not how we've done things

00:25:28.020 --> 00:25:34.420
[Guest]: We've just kind of so before we increase the budget for these things. I really would like to see more efficient spending also

00:25:35.140 --> 00:25:41.860
[Guest]: so so I I think that um sustaining that progress, you know, of course I talked about the number of things that happened that led

00:25:42.240 --> 00:25:49.380
[Guest]: ultimately to our terrible defeat, but I think we should have paid more attention to sustaining that progress and

00:25:49.380 --> 00:25:54.900
[Guest]: And we should have also been more careful about the sugar high. We had to kind of calibrate that better

00:25:54.980 --> 00:25:59.300
[Guest]: I think we we did not and frankly i'm not in a position to tell why that

00:25:59.940 --> 00:26:03.780
[Guest]: May have been the case what they were thinking at that time. I was in the us at that time

00:26:04.100 --> 00:26:06.660
[Guest]: I can tell you that at the world bank and the imf we were

00:26:07.140 --> 00:26:10.820
[Guest]: Very very worried extremely worried that the global economy was falling off a cliff

00:26:11.380 --> 00:26:13.540
[Guest]: And everybody was panicking frankly

00:26:13.540 --> 00:26:18.900
[Guest]: So I can't I can imagine that in india the policy makers must have been like wondering

00:26:19.220 --> 00:26:22.900
[Guest]: What can we do to save this crisis off and they they did what they did

00:26:23.220 --> 00:26:27.540
[Guest]: But I wonder if we put enough thought into how progress could be sustained

00:26:27.780 --> 00:26:34.900
[Guest]: Maybe we could have gone with a slightly lower growth and then uh, you know, uh, that meant smaller fiscal stimulus

00:26:35.460 --> 00:26:38.580
[Guest]: Uh, maybe calibrated that better of course, uh,

00:26:38.580 --> 00:26:43.700
[Guest]: The scandals that hit us. I mean, you know, that is something that and the other thing is that if the scandals hit us

00:26:44.260 --> 00:26:45.540
[Guest]: Where is the accountability?

00:26:45.540 --> 00:26:51.620
[Guest]: So I think that we don't really have accountability mechanisms that are that really, you know, we should have something right?

00:26:51.620 --> 00:26:56.740
[Guest]: I mean something happened and uh, but uh, even this comment has not been able to kind of

00:26:57.700 --> 00:27:01.140
[Guest]: Hold people accountable. Uh, and uh, so I think it's all about

00:27:01.940 --> 00:27:06.180
[Guest]: Political kind of maneuvering then uh, so keeping people bogged down

00:27:06.180 --> 00:27:12.020
[Guest]: But i'm afraid that's not the way, you know, india can reach its potential. I just don't I had a recent episode with

00:27:12.580 --> 00:27:17.060
[Amit Varma]: Pooja Mehra recently where you know, we spoke about the political economy of those years in a fair bit of detail

00:27:17.060 --> 00:27:19.060
[Amit Varma]: I'll put that link on my episode page for the listeners

00:27:19.300 --> 00:27:22.500
[Amit Varma]: Uh, you know just a brief detour on education while you were talking about that

00:27:22.500 --> 00:27:27.140
[Amit Varma]: I think one thing that both parties have consistently gone got wrong on education is something that in fact

00:27:27.460 --> 00:27:30.020
[Amit Varma]: You referred to at the start as something that you know

00:27:30.020 --> 00:27:33.860
[Amit Varma]: The world bank taught you not to do which is to focus on inputs instead of outcomes

00:27:33.860 --> 00:27:40.100
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you you had the bjp in the 2014 manifesto saying we'll spend six percent of gdp on education

00:27:40.100 --> 00:27:42.100
[Amit Varma]: And I think the congress made a similar promise

00:27:42.340 --> 00:27:47.620
[Amit Varma]: Uh this time but that's just looking at the input and outputs are miserable and for that you need to look partly

00:27:48.020 --> 00:27:53.540
[Amit Varma]: At the way education is structured the incentives in play the fact that the private sector is completely

00:27:54.100 --> 00:27:55.700
[Amit Varma]: shut out through

00:27:55.700 --> 00:28:00.660
[Amit Varma]: You know an immense amount of over regulation, but you know, leaving that leaving that aside

00:28:00.660 --> 00:28:04.900
[Amit Varma]: There's a broader philosophical question really that I wanted to ask you about the political economy

00:28:04.900 --> 00:28:06.900
[Amit Varma]: That doesn't apply to this party or to that party

00:28:07.140 --> 00:28:11.300
[Amit Varma]: But you know the thought came to me when I uh, i'll just quote from your book

00:28:11.300 --> 00:28:14.980
[Amit Varma]: You quote these economists quote while ghatak and ghosh who pointed out. Um

00:28:15.700 --> 00:28:18.100
[Amit Varma]: About what the upa was going through in 2014

00:28:18.500 --> 00:28:24.500
[Amit Varma]: Quote, it is a unique misfortune for any party to be charged with both crony capitalism and unbridled welfarism

00:28:25.300 --> 00:28:28.340
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote and uh, you know the thought that came to me was that

00:28:28.340 --> 00:28:35.700
[Amit Varma]: This is actually an inevitable accusation for any government become because of the imperatives of politics on the one hand

00:28:36.100 --> 00:28:42.820
[Amit Varma]: You have interest groups who have funded you whom you have to satisfy. So crony capitalism seems inevitable and on the other hand

00:28:43.380 --> 00:28:45.620
[Amit Varma]: You know, you need to buy vote banks

00:28:45.620 --> 00:28:50.500
[Amit Varma]: So you need to appeal to voters and the populism that leads to welfarism also seems inevitable

00:28:50.820 --> 00:28:54.580
[Amit Varma]: So just as a broader question not as a member of one party or any party

00:28:54.580 --> 00:29:00.100
[Amit Varma]: Because I think this is a dilemma that the whole political system faces. How does one get past this?

00:29:00.980 --> 00:29:02.980
[Amit Varma]: The analogy to this is the following

00:29:04.420 --> 00:29:06.420
[Guest]: When you talk about somebody who's a reformer

00:29:07.220 --> 00:29:12.660
[Guest]: They say do you want reforms? Do you want someone who's a pro business person? Or do you want someone who's a pro market person?

00:29:13.460 --> 00:29:18.420
[Guest]: From my perspective pro market, right? You don't want to be pro business. You don't want anybody to be pro business

00:29:19.060 --> 00:29:21.060
[Guest]: You want somebody to be pro business?

00:29:21.060 --> 00:29:25.700
[Guest]: You don't want anybody to be pro business. You want somebody to create a level playing field?

00:29:25.700 --> 00:29:30.980
[Guest]: You want markets to flourish and then people can compete that is what I've learned in my life

00:29:31.060 --> 00:29:35.460
[Guest]: That is what my training is. I don't know. I think the evidence indicates that

00:29:36.100 --> 00:29:38.100
[Guest]: That is where people should be

00:29:38.340 --> 00:29:42.180
[Guest]: Make these markets let them grow let them flourish and let people compete

00:29:43.060 --> 00:29:46.100
[Guest]: Don't try to pick winners. Don't try to support one

00:29:46.980 --> 00:29:48.980
[Guest]: business versus another

00:29:48.980 --> 00:29:53.160
[Guest]: Similarly as far as you know, you want to promote capitalism. Yes

00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:59.320
[Guest]: But crony capitalism is this kind of disease that that is just not going to allow you to

00:30:00.040 --> 00:30:05.000
[Guest]: Make decisions that would help you become a pro market reformer

00:30:05.480 --> 00:30:07.960
[Guest]: So it's all very well to say, you know

00:30:07.960 --> 00:30:11.800
[Guest]: We need funding and we need funding to kind of fight elections because that's what we need

00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:16.280
[Guest]: And then we can once we are in government, we can kind of do welfare politics. The trouble is

00:30:16.280 --> 00:30:23.080
[Guest]: It doesn't really work that way in reality what what happens ultimately is that these interest groups

00:30:23.160 --> 00:30:30.520
[Guest]: They capture it's part of this elite capture, right? I mean, there is a reason we have high inequality in india and growing

00:30:31.160 --> 00:30:35.160
[Guest]: And that is because we we are perhaps not

00:30:35.960 --> 00:30:40.600
[Guest]: Leveling the playing field. We're not supporting markets. We may be supporting mr

00:30:40.600 --> 00:30:46.840
[Guest]: X we may be supporting mr. X or mrs. Y because they may fund us through through whatever means

00:30:47.400 --> 00:30:51.960
[Guest]: Uh, but we never tell people exactly what they're doing, uh, you know for us

00:30:52.600 --> 00:30:54.600
[Guest]: So as a citizen, I want to know

00:30:55.400 --> 00:31:01.720
[Guest]: Who is paying the government off and what is the government doing in return for this person?

00:31:03.080 --> 00:31:04.760
[Guest]: We don't know

00:31:04.760 --> 00:31:08.520
[Guest]: We simply don't know and I don't i'm not blaming the multi-government for this or you know

00:31:08.520 --> 00:31:12.840
[Guest]: This is like a cross-government kind of thing now with electoral bonds

00:31:13.400 --> 00:31:16.300
[Guest]: It's kind of legalized corruption to my mind. This is legalized corruption

00:31:16.840 --> 00:31:18.840
[Guest]: We can't have these kinds of things

00:31:18.840 --> 00:31:24.200
[Guest]: If we can't see the destitution in which so many millions of indians live

00:31:25.560 --> 00:31:30.600
[Guest]: And then we don't correlate that with what is happening at the upper levels upper income levels

00:31:31.560 --> 00:31:36.460
[Guest]: Then we're just basically saying okay, you know what it's good to have you know, at least we see that some people are progressing

00:31:36.460 --> 00:31:41.820
[Guest]: But that is not a model that india can really work with but that is a model that we're working with

00:31:42.700 --> 00:31:43.900
[Guest]: and

00:31:43.900 --> 00:31:50.620
[Guest]: This cronyism is is a special kind of disease. I mean, why can't our corporates they already have a lead, right?

00:31:50.700 --> 00:31:52.460
[Guest]: They're already running ahead

00:31:52.460 --> 00:31:54.780
[Guest]: Why can't they just uh, you know

00:31:55.660 --> 00:31:57.820
[Guest]: Uh, if they want to contribute to a party

00:31:58.540 --> 00:32:04.300
[Guest]: Fine contribute tell people what you're doing and then we'll see whether there is any uh quid pro quo

00:32:05.260 --> 00:32:06.300
[Guest]: but

00:32:06.300 --> 00:32:09.740
[Guest]: You already have a lead and you want you want to pad that lead

00:32:10.380 --> 00:32:11.260
[Guest]: through

