[Guest]: It's not my fault, but I have to rescue this country. I have to rescue that's what i'm here for

01:07:40.060 --> 01:07:43.180
[Guest]: I don't think people would have blamed it. I think people would have been happy

01:07:43.180 --> 01:07:46.620
[Guest]: I mean they would have at least given him a chance in a similar vein if he had said

01:07:46.620 --> 01:07:52.300
[Guest]: You know what air india has been bleeding money for a long time. This is not a viable way to do business

01:07:53.100 --> 01:07:55.100
[Guest]: It doesn't seem to be working

01:07:55.420 --> 01:07:59.660
[Guest]: I have said myself that we we've been to kind of uh, reform some of these things

01:08:00.060 --> 01:08:02.860
[Guest]: We're going to sell this thing off. I don't think people would have said

01:08:03.660 --> 01:08:09.180
[Guest]: Modi you're wrong. They would have you know said okay, you know, he came to reform things and he's reforming reforming things

01:08:09.180 --> 01:08:13.820
[Guest]: But as I write in the book people did not believe that he was a reformer of that sort

01:08:13.820 --> 01:08:18.140
[Guest]: In fact, I don't think he believes in a smaller public sector, you know

01:08:18.780 --> 01:08:22.540
[Guest]: I believe in a more efficient public sector. I believe in a more

01:08:23.100 --> 01:08:28.380
[Guest]: Constrained public sector because I want the government to focus on things that the private sector is not able to deliver properly

01:08:29.180 --> 01:08:33.980
[Guest]: The private sector cannot deliver your national defense the private private sector will not to my mind

01:08:34.540 --> 01:08:37.340
[Guest]: Do a good job with you know, say

01:08:37.340 --> 01:08:40.380
[Guest]: Police forces or justice and all the stuff, right?

01:08:40.940 --> 01:08:42.940
[Guest]: I don't think he believes that I think he's just

01:08:43.660 --> 01:08:46.540
[Guest]: He thinks that government can do everything and his government can do everything

01:08:47.500 --> 01:08:51.500
[Guest]: So maybe I should not be puzzled after all these years. I think that's who he is

01:08:52.060 --> 01:08:57.660
[Guest]: I don't think you know and by the way, that's what maybe most politicians in india think that we should have these kinds of

01:08:58.220 --> 01:09:03.340
[Guest]: Things in air india is great and you know, we should have a flag carrier and all this stuff. I don't know

01:09:03.340 --> 01:09:07.820
[Guest]: I think people may think like that. I personally do not believe that taxpayer money

01:09:08.460 --> 01:09:14.220
[Guest]: Should be spent when there is no hope of you know, recovery in some of these enterprises

01:09:14.540 --> 01:09:20.300
[Guest]: Now there are some things where you really need big public sector kind of giants to kind of

01:09:21.020 --> 01:09:26.380
[Guest]: Do certain types of businesses they can be strategic in nature other countries have them too and they do they seem to do well

01:09:26.700 --> 01:09:28.700
[Guest]: They some of them are doing well in india as well

01:09:28.700 --> 01:09:33.340
[Guest]: But I can't make that case for most of them. I think so if I can't make that case for most of them

01:09:33.340 --> 01:09:36.140
[Guest]: You know, you know what my feeling would be about disinvestment

01:09:36.460 --> 01:09:41.820
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean I I often make the case that what india needs is a strong and limited government that does a few things

01:09:41.820 --> 01:09:45.740
[Amit Varma]: Very well instead of a large and diffuse government that does nothing well

01:09:45.740 --> 01:09:49.100
[Amit Varma]: I mean we effectively don't have a rule of law in most of the country

01:09:49.260 --> 01:09:54.700
[Amit Varma]: You know, I I did an episode recently with puja mara who's also written a book about by the same publisher the last decade

01:09:54.700 --> 01:09:56.700
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, uh, she talks about the

01:09:56.700 --> 01:10:02.860
[Amit Varma]: Modi years and the and the point that she kind of makes was that it was political imperatives that caused him number one to move

01:10:02.860 --> 01:10:08.860
[Amit Varma]: Away from reforms because many of these reforms were complicated thing around which you couldn't build a simple narrative

01:10:08.860 --> 01:10:15.660
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, why bother if there's no short-term political payoff and at the same time which drew him towards

01:10:16.220 --> 01:10:23.900
[Amit Varma]: Disasters like demonetization for example, not because of what impact it would have which he didn't give a damn about but because of how it could

01:10:23.900 --> 01:10:29.340
[Amit Varma]: Be packaged as something that is anti-black money and will help the poor and so on and so forth

01:10:29.660 --> 01:10:36.620
[Amit Varma]: And how far do you think modi was driven purely by political imperatives and and you know that

01:10:37.820 --> 01:10:40.140
[Amit Varma]: Was responsible for what has happened?

01:10:40.780 --> 01:10:45.100
[Guest]: I think uh, modi is nothing if he's not a political animal. I think uh,

01:10:45.660 --> 01:10:49.180
[Guest]: Clearly, uh politics plays a large role in

01:10:49.180 --> 01:10:53.820
[Guest]: The decisions he's taken. I think in that sense puja is right, you know

01:10:54.460 --> 01:11:00.860
[Guest]: Politics did drive say demonetization because it was packaged as a hit against black money and all that

01:11:01.500 --> 01:11:03.500
[Guest]: Then you know the question is

01:11:04.380 --> 01:11:06.380
[Guest]: then

01:11:06.380 --> 01:11:08.380
[Guest]: Basically, we were all kind of

01:11:09.020 --> 01:11:15.660
[Guest]: Hoping for something that would never happen because if a person like that who by all accounts is you know

01:11:15.660 --> 01:11:22.060
[Guest]: Liked for his oratory and all that and can convince people to go with him pretty much

01:11:22.700 --> 01:11:27.500
[Guest]: Very often or at least used to be if that person is not going to kind of

01:11:28.300 --> 01:11:31.740
[Guest]: Level with the country and say look this makes sense to me

01:11:32.620 --> 01:11:34.620
[Guest]: We are wasting

01:11:34.620 --> 01:11:36.140
[Guest]: the hardened

01:11:36.140 --> 01:11:39.260
[Guest]: Taxpayer money on things that we should not be spending on

01:11:39.980 --> 01:11:43.500
[Guest]: Then in that sense, we never really want us, you know, we should then be

01:11:43.500 --> 01:11:49.580
[Guest]: Careful about what we uh think of in the future. We should basically be hoping for coalition governments, honestly

01:11:50.140 --> 01:11:53.740
[Guest]: Because we don't really need a strong central character because a strong central character

01:11:54.380 --> 01:11:56.540
[Guest]: Can be much more destructive for india

01:11:57.100 --> 01:11:59.420
[Guest]: With the weight for this benign dictator

01:11:59.980 --> 01:12:04.220
[Guest]: Can take a lifetime and who knows how that will pan out and these things don't pan out

01:12:04.220 --> 01:12:08.940
[Guest]: Well now in modi's case, I really thought that he might make some decisions which

01:12:08.940 --> 01:12:12.940
[Guest]: I mean what what is tough about you know, telling the country that you know

01:12:13.020 --> 01:12:17.900
[Guest]: The upa gave me a bad deal on banks and I need to fix it. Otherwise, you will not have jobs

01:12:18.460 --> 01:12:21.580
[Guest]: That's a pretty simple argument to make I think people would have believed it

01:12:22.060 --> 01:12:25.660
[Guest]: It was just that he was not focused on that. I think he was focused on

01:12:26.200 --> 01:12:31.020
[Guest]: Administrative efficiency and how projects that were stalled would move forward. I think he was thinking small

01:12:31.820 --> 01:12:35.740
[Guest]: He was not thinking big. He was really I think he was thinking very small

01:12:35.740 --> 01:12:40.460
[Guest]: So somebody must have told him that you know, if we have a higher tax, people are not paying taxes

01:12:40.700 --> 01:12:42.700
[Guest]: We need to increase the tax revenues

01:12:43.180 --> 01:12:48.460
[Guest]: So yeah, okay, you know, let's let's go after that. But that's thinking small. That's not thinking broad

01:12:49.340 --> 01:12:52.140
[Guest]: That's not thinking big. So I don't know maybe he's uh,

01:12:52.780 --> 01:12:55.260
[Guest]: He's a victim of uh his own kind of

01:12:55.980 --> 01:13:02.780
[Guest]: Ambitions in terms of in policy. Maybe he's a small, you know, he has a narrow base to think on

01:13:02.780 --> 01:13:06.220
[Guest]: I think that's the only explanation I can come up with. I I don't really know

01:13:06.940 --> 01:13:13.980
[Guest]: Why he did not make even the simplest no, it's some easy decisions. I don't know. I don't get it

01:13:14.140 --> 01:13:18.220
[Guest]: I'm honestly i'm puzzled right, you know, and i'm just thinking aloud here

01:13:18.220 --> 01:13:23.420
[Amit Varma]: It's something that a friend of mine who was very close to modi once upon a time in his gujarati years once told me

01:13:23.980 --> 01:13:28.780
[Amit Varma]: And she mentioned how there was a social gathering at his house and he started to

01:13:28.780 --> 01:13:32.780
[Amit Varma]: Telling a story at one point about how when he was a kid his mother was very ill

01:13:33.340 --> 01:13:36.780
[Amit Varma]: And he was a boy then and he went to switch on the fan

01:13:37.100 --> 01:13:40.080
[Amit Varma]: And when he flicked the switch he realized that there was no electricity

01:13:40.380 --> 01:13:43.920
[Amit Varma]: And then he decided that if there's one thing I can do i'll focus on electricity

01:13:44.220 --> 01:13:49.740
[Amit Varma]: And therefore when he becomes cm of gujarat, you know, he focuses on electrification and all my friends point in telling me

01:13:49.740 --> 01:13:54.220
[Amit Varma]: The story basically was that his view of the world is very experiential

01:13:54.220 --> 01:13:59.040
[Amit Varma]: If he has experienced something directly then he gives it importance like the lack of electricity

01:13:59.340 --> 01:14:05.120
[Amit Varma]: Or roads or so on those physical things where he can see with his own eyes that yes, this makes a difference

01:14:05.740 --> 01:14:12.060
[Amit Varma]: But for a man who doesn't apparently read too many books either when it comes to higher abstract concepts

01:14:12.060 --> 01:14:15.180
[Amit Varma]: Which you need to grasp when you talk about how an economy functions

01:14:15.660 --> 01:14:18.860
[Amit Varma]: Especially when so many of the fundamental economic truths you and I know like

01:14:18.860 --> 01:14:25.900
[Amit Varma]: You know like all trade being positive some instead of zero some or spontaneous order the way markets organize themselves

01:14:26.300 --> 01:14:29.980
[Amit Varma]: All of these higher level concepts is not something he would ever have grasped

01:14:30.860 --> 01:14:34.460
[Amit Varma]: Because he hasn't experienced it directly and he has no way of doing so

01:14:34.780 --> 01:14:39.580
[Amit Varma]: And and for this reason I sometimes call him the akhodeki prime minister and again i'm just speculating here

01:14:40.940 --> 01:14:44.460
[Amit Varma]: Do you think there is something to this that he has no way of doing so?

01:14:44.460 --> 01:14:50.940
[Amit Varma]: And again, i'm just speculating here. Do you think there is something to this that I mean in the sense that a politician

01:14:51.100 --> 01:14:58.300
[Amit Varma]: Therefore also needs to be well read and well versed in abstract ideas. So you get a better sense of all of this

01:14:59.340 --> 01:15:05.660
[Guest]: Uh, you know, you can't wing economic development, you know, this is uh, this is far too complex

01:15:06.140 --> 01:15:08.880
[Guest]: I mean anybody who who basically decides to do demonetization

01:15:09.580 --> 01:15:13.760
[Guest]: Has clearly not spent much time thinking about policies and their implications

01:15:13.760 --> 01:15:16.640
[Guest]: You know, I think you're right. You may find it easier to say look

01:15:17.200 --> 01:15:19.360
[Guest]: There's open defecation. I'm going to build more toilets

01:15:20.960 --> 01:15:28.080
[Guest]: We need more girls education because that's what i've been told is, you know, we need more girls education where i'm studying or

01:15:28.800 --> 01:15:32.720
[Guest]: There's no busily here and I would need to kind of flick a switch and so that there's power

01:15:33.280 --> 01:15:35.280
[Guest]: I think yes, but uh

01:15:35.840 --> 01:15:39.680
[Guest]: In today's world policy making is so complex. There's so much going on

01:15:39.680 --> 01:15:44.960
[Guest]: There are so many you press one button and something else goes wrong and then you're trying to control for that and you can't control

01:15:45.040 --> 01:15:46.400
[Guest]: for that and

01:15:46.400 --> 01:15:51.680
[Guest]: You know, not everything is in your own kind of hands. You will have quantitative easing in the u.s

01:15:51.760 --> 01:15:53.760
[Guest]: That'll have an impact on your currency

01:15:54.000 --> 01:15:57.920
[Guest]: Uh, you that'll have an impact on flows of capital

01:15:58.480 --> 01:16:01.120
[Guest]: So you need obviously no single person

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:04.080
[Guest]: Would have all that experience clearly

01:16:04.640 --> 01:16:05.600
[Guest]: uh

01:16:05.600 --> 01:16:07.600
[Guest]: But you should have some basic

01:16:07.600 --> 01:16:11.280
[Guest]: Uh humility to know that you don't know everything

01:16:11.520 --> 01:16:17.920
[Guest]: That's one second that you build a team or you have a team of people advisors and all that who can kind of

01:16:19.040 --> 01:16:21.040
[Guest]: Give you different perspectives

01:16:21.120 --> 01:16:23.040
[Guest]: You must listen. You should be a good listener

01:16:23.040 --> 01:16:28.720
[Guest]: I think and you should be willing to take advice and you should be willing to say, you know what i'm wrong. This is not

01:16:29.840 --> 01:16:33.280
[Guest]: I thought of it in the incorrect way. This expertise is really

01:16:33.280 --> 01:16:41.040
[Guest]: Uh useful here, but I don't think you know from what I gather. I don't think people are that keen to give him advice

01:16:41.600 --> 01:16:44.080
[Guest]: Because maybe they're scared of giving him advice

01:16:44.880 --> 01:16:46.880
[Guest]: Or maybe he doesn't listen to advice who knows?

01:16:47.040 --> 01:16:53.280
[Guest]: I mean if you can do demonetization without taking the rbi or your finance minister into confidence, which is alleged

01:16:53.920 --> 01:16:56.640
[Guest]: Then then you know that we're in trouble, right? I mean

01:16:58.240 --> 01:16:59.120
[Guest]: So

01:16:59.120 --> 01:17:02.560
[Guest]: Yeah, you may be right about this experiential kind of uh instinct

01:17:02.560 --> 01:17:08.160
[Guest]: But you know making policy based on that because those are things that you can do you can deliver

01:17:08.640 --> 01:17:10.640
[Guest]: but in terms of if you cannot

01:17:11.040 --> 01:17:17.120
[Guest]: In economic development in in governance in policy making you have to have a broad-based team

01:17:17.600 --> 01:17:23.440
[Guest]: Uh who can actually help inform you who can help educate you and you know, that would be anybody

01:17:23.440 --> 01:17:28.800
[Guest]: It's not just you know tomorrow. I mean you could be the prime minister of the country, but even you would need tons of

01:17:28.800 --> 01:17:34.960
[Guest]: You know support no matter how broad-based your economic training has been so I think in that sense he too

01:17:35.760 --> 01:17:41.120
[Guest]: You know, I think needs a lot of help. I'm not sure he thinks he needs it, but I I do think he needs it

01:17:41.280 --> 01:17:42.480
[Amit Varma]: I mean, yeah, as I said earlier

01:17:42.480 --> 01:17:47.360
[Amit Varma]: I think the most important quality for anybody in a position of power is epistemic humility

01:17:47.440 --> 01:17:51.280
[Amit Varma]: And and that's something that we've kind of consistently lacked you've you know

01:17:51.360 --> 01:17:56.880
[Amit Varma]: So you've got a couple of great chapters on what the policies and programs of the government were and what the results were and i'll just

01:17:56.880 --> 01:18:00.720
[Amit Varma]: Encourage all my listeners to um buy the book and read that there's some great

01:18:01.280 --> 01:18:04.080
[Amit Varma]: Detail in there. I want to sort of stick to broader questions

01:18:04.320 --> 01:18:08.240
[Amit Varma]: One of which being what did he get right in that time? I know that's a hard question

01:18:09.600 --> 01:18:11.600
[Guest]: No, no, I mean, you know

01:18:11.680 --> 01:18:18.800
[Guest]: To my mind some of the things that I think he deserves a good credit for is something like bringing attention

01:18:19.360 --> 01:18:21.040
[Guest]: to you know

01:18:21.040 --> 01:18:27.040
[Guest]: Clean india right swachh bharat. I think that kind of personal attention and relentless attention

01:18:27.120 --> 01:18:31.840
[Guest]: I think that's a kind of a national level kind of even I mean forget what happens on the ground and all this

01:18:32.080 --> 01:18:34.080
[Guest]: just creating awareness, I think

01:18:34.160 --> 01:18:38.400
[Guest]: Leaders should be creating awareness about issues of national importance

01:18:38.800 --> 01:18:40.800
[Guest]: Uh, you know educating the girl child

01:18:42.640 --> 01:18:47.520
[Guest]: These kinds of things are I think these are things that are aspirational in some ways for a country like india

01:18:47.520 --> 01:18:52.160
[Guest]: And it's good to kind of you know for leaders to kind of wear their

01:18:52.640 --> 01:18:56.560
[Guest]: Kind of thoughts on their sleeves in some ways and say look this is important to me

01:18:56.800 --> 01:18:59.360
[Guest]: I really want and especially if you're a popular leader and you

01:18:59.920 --> 01:19:04.960
[Guest]: Use your popularity to kind of bring awareness because a lot of the times we're simply not aware

01:19:05.760 --> 01:19:09.360
[Guest]: Despite all the smartphones and technology and everything

01:19:09.680 --> 01:19:15.120
[Guest]: Most people you know, we just we get used to seeing things from our own perspective. We never kind of

