[Guest]: It's hard for us to kind of you know

01:19:17.360 --> 01:19:22.560
[Guest]: Look at things from a broader perspective and having a leader like that talk about these kinds of issues

01:19:22.560 --> 01:19:25.760
[Guest]: I think is very very important and I think it's very helpful

01:19:26.560 --> 01:19:31.120
[Guest]: So I would say on these kinds of issues. I have kind of in my book also going to said that yes

01:19:31.840 --> 01:19:37.840
[Guest]: He's talked a good game and he's kind of uh led on these and I think he should get credit for these kinds of things

01:19:37.840 --> 01:19:39.120
[Guest]: um

01:19:39.120 --> 01:19:41.280
[Guest]: You know coming up with these indices for cities

01:19:41.280 --> 01:19:44.880
[Guest]: Which one is clean which is not, you know may not pay immediate dividends

01:19:44.880 --> 01:19:51.360
[Guest]: But ultimately may prove that there's some competition and you know, maybe it may help cities to kind of you know

01:19:51.680 --> 01:19:55.600
[Guest]: Take pride in the work that they're doing in terms of keeping the cities clean

01:19:56.160 --> 01:19:59.040
[Guest]: Creating a more welcoming kind of environment for people

01:19:59.680 --> 01:20:04.480
[Guest]: Um, he's talked a good game on tourism and but you know, uh in terms of you know

01:20:05.040 --> 01:20:08.800
[Guest]: Ease of visas and all that stuff making india feel more welcome

01:20:08.800 --> 01:20:12.320
[Guest]: But you know, of course the other the flip side is that we need to do a lot more on

01:20:12.960 --> 01:20:21.440
[Guest]: Safety, I think that has fallen by the wayside because you know, we need uh, we our police is still a force not a service

01:20:22.240 --> 01:20:27.760
[Guest]: And I think there I think that it's both a positive in terms of trying to create a better image for india

01:20:27.760 --> 01:20:31.360
[Guest]: But at the same time not doing the basics that are needed. So you

01:20:31.920 --> 01:20:36.960
[Guest]: You know that that's the kind of I sometimes get frustrated why this whole good talk

01:20:36.960 --> 01:20:42.720
[Guest]: Aspirational talk and then under delivery of the basics. I think that's where I feel

01:20:43.760 --> 01:20:45.920
[Guest]: A little bit of frustration with the government

01:20:46.560 --> 01:20:49.680
[Guest]: But there are other things too, you know, they did finally push through ibc

01:20:50.560 --> 01:20:53.440
[Guest]: Yes, they did the gst. Of course the gst is a mess

01:20:54.000 --> 01:20:55.920
[Guest]: But at least uh, you know

01:20:55.920 --> 01:20:57.920
[Guest]: He was able to push it through now

01:20:57.920 --> 01:20:59.280
[Guest]: We'll have to kind of you know

01:20:59.280 --> 01:21:02.000
[Guest]: Now we have it in the constitutional framework and now we can kind of maybe

01:21:02.000 --> 01:21:08.400
[Guest]: Do wholesale reform not once and for all but at least in a major way. I think ibc happened a bit

01:21:08.960 --> 01:21:15.600
[Guest]: Late in my view, but even then I think ibc is now hampered. Uh, I mean, you know the bankruptcy code

01:21:16.160 --> 01:21:19.040
[Guest]: I don't know if how well that is being implemented right now

01:21:19.600 --> 01:21:23.760
[Guest]: I don't know but at least you know he moved on that ease of doing business. I think

01:21:24.320 --> 01:21:26.320
[Guest]: Frankly, they're trying to game the system

01:21:26.880 --> 01:21:29.040
[Guest]: Genuinely ease of doing business would be when everybody

01:21:29.040 --> 01:21:32.960
[Guest]: Around the country would feel that yes, it's easier to do business. I don't think that's happening. I think because

01:21:33.520 --> 01:21:38.480
[Guest]: There's more coercion these days i'm told on businesses than used to be the case

01:21:38.960 --> 01:21:41.760
[Guest]: So even though the world bank has recognized india

01:21:42.320 --> 01:21:46.640
[Guest]: As having done a lot on ease of doing business. I think that may be more

01:21:47.200 --> 01:21:51.760
[Guest]: Through gaming the system, you know putin once told his officials that he wanted russia to be

01:21:52.320 --> 01:21:54.320
[Guest]: In the top 30 by a certain number of years

01:21:54.320 --> 01:21:59.200
[Guest]: And I think they're all scurrying to figure out how they would do it within the stipulated time and they did it

01:21:59.760 --> 01:22:03.280
[Guest]: So, you know when you have the threat of putin, uh, hanging over your head

01:22:03.840 --> 01:22:06.240
[Guest]: You can you can do that and I think in modi's case too

01:22:07.120 --> 01:22:08.720
[Guest]: They managed to gain this

01:22:08.720 --> 01:22:10.720
[Guest]: I think managed to gain the system a little bit

01:22:11.280 --> 01:22:16.240
[Guest]: But honestly, I don't think there's a lot that i'm happy about. I really think this is a missed opportunity

01:22:16.960 --> 01:22:18.720
[Guest]: really missed opportunity

01:22:18.720 --> 01:22:21.520
[Guest]: And uh people like you and I will be okay

01:22:21.520 --> 01:22:24.960
[Guest]: But people who could have benefited disproportionately, I think they're not going to be okay

01:22:25.280 --> 01:22:28.960
[Amit Varma]: So before I ask you about you know, the state of the economy today just a tangential thought

01:22:28.960 --> 01:22:33.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, obviously you're right about uh, you know when I saw the eodb, uh, the things I figured that yeah

01:22:33.600 --> 01:22:35.680
[Amit Varma]: Wherever there are metrics, they can be gamed

01:22:35.680 --> 01:22:40.800
[Amit Varma]: So this is like an evolving game where you have to keep taking the metrics deeper and deeper

01:22:40.960 --> 01:22:45.200
[Amit Varma]: But so here's a tangential question because you mentioned the ibc the bankruptcy code

01:22:45.360 --> 01:22:49.520
[Amit Varma]: That where it's apparently at is that while the ibc is not in the market

01:22:49.520 --> 01:22:52.400
[Amit Varma]: But where it's apparently at is that while the ibc is a welcome

01:22:53.040 --> 01:22:56.880
[Amit Varma]: Uh reform where we are stuck is that state capacity simply isn't enough

01:22:56.880 --> 01:23:00.560
[Amit Varma]: So now now because of state capacity not being enough you're kind of stuck now

01:23:00.560 --> 01:23:05.860
[Amit Varma]: You're someone who could hopefully, you know, maybe be in government one day and in a position to carry out reforms

01:23:06.720 --> 01:23:11.860
[Amit Varma]: When you are in that position besides the immediate considerations of the political economy

01:23:12.160 --> 01:23:17.120
[Amit Varma]: Do you also have to take into account whether there is enough state capacity for those reforms to happen at all?

01:23:17.120 --> 01:23:20.800
[Guest]: Oh, yeah. Yeah, absolutely. I I I mentioned it earlier in this

01:23:21.440 --> 01:23:27.280
[Guest]: We've limited capacity, you know, we we talk about our civil service officers and how hard they're working and all this stuff

01:23:27.600 --> 01:23:33.520
[Guest]: But for the most part in government, and by the way, when we talk about government, we're not talking about just the central government

01:23:33.520 --> 01:23:37.360
[Guest]: We're talking about state governments as well. The public sector is very limited capacity

01:23:37.840 --> 01:23:43.840
[Guest]: So, uh when you try to implement things it takes so much more effort so much more time, you know, I was just recently

01:23:44.560 --> 01:23:46.000
[Guest]: visited

01:23:46.000 --> 01:23:48.000
[Guest]: um the Hoover Dam

01:23:48.000 --> 01:23:50.000
[Guest]: in Nevada in the US

01:23:50.400 --> 01:23:52.320
[Guest]: Nevada slash Arizona

01:23:52.320 --> 01:23:56.980
[Guest]: the Hoover Dam in was uh built from 1931 to 1935

01:23:57.600 --> 01:24:00.180
[Guest]: In you know, just around the time of the depression

01:24:00.800 --> 01:24:02.560
[Guest]: in five years roughly

01:24:02.560 --> 01:24:05.280
[Guest]: There's a flyover and Hoover Dam is huge

01:24:06.000 --> 01:24:08.740
[Guest]: There's a flyover in Hyderpore of Srinagar

01:24:08.740 --> 01:24:15.700
[Guest]: Which was built over seven years the length of the flyover is maybe about a kilometer less than that

01:24:15.860 --> 01:24:18.180
[Guest]: It's not even a flyover. It's a kind of an overpass

01:24:18.980 --> 01:24:22.740
[Guest]: Hoover Dam five to six years and this flyover

01:24:23.620 --> 01:24:25.620
[Guest]: Seven years a small little thing

01:24:26.580 --> 01:24:29.060
[Guest]: This flyover was built in the 2000s

01:24:29.940 --> 01:24:32.900
[Guest]: Now imagine where we are look at the difference now

01:24:32.900 --> 01:24:37.620
[Guest]: You can't say that we we didn't have resources because we clearly had resources because we built the flyover

01:24:37.620 --> 01:24:41.380
[Guest]: But how is it possible that in a modern state?

01:24:41.860 --> 01:24:45.620
[Guest]: It takes seven years to build a one kilometer long flyover in Srinagar

01:24:46.180 --> 01:24:48.180
[Guest]: Whereas somebody built a huge dam

01:24:48.180 --> 01:24:50.180
[Guest]: major irrigation project

01:24:50.180 --> 01:24:52.180
[Guest]: major power generation project

01:24:52.340 --> 01:24:54.340
[Guest]: in the 1930s

01:24:54.340 --> 01:24:57.700
[Guest]: I think we need to recognize that we are still limited

01:24:58.340 --> 01:25:01.780
[Guest]: And in some ways when you craft policies, you have to keep that in mind

01:25:01.780 --> 01:25:06.500
[Guest]: If you don't keep that in mind, you'll have implementation disaster after implementation disaster

01:25:06.500 --> 01:25:11.460
[Guest]: And and that is why I think I'm at your point of doing a few things really well

01:25:12.420 --> 01:25:14.420
[Guest]: I think that's important

01:25:14.420 --> 01:25:17.860
[Guest]: Let's just do a few things, but let's let the government do them really well

01:25:18.660 --> 01:25:22.660
[Guest]: Let there be a contract between we call it the social contract in some ways between

01:25:23.220 --> 01:25:28.580
[Guest]: The citizen and the state and say you know what you want to do schools. You want to do education public education?

01:25:28.580 --> 01:25:33.300
[Guest]: Yeah, okay, but we want you to deliver along these parameters

01:25:33.300 --> 01:25:40.580
[Guest]: These are the indicators of success. These are the learning outcomes we want. This is how we want our children to grow

01:25:41.220 --> 01:25:43.220
[Guest]: If we could have that

01:25:43.300 --> 01:25:47.300
[Guest]: I mean, I refer to the PISA kind of system of

01:25:48.020 --> 01:25:51.860
[Guest]: Testing across countries as far as education attainment is concerned

01:25:52.580 --> 01:25:54.900
[Guest]: I think the last time it was done under the UPA government

01:25:55.460 --> 01:26:00.500
[Guest]: Then we abandoned it because our kids from I think Tamil Nadu and Himachal Pradesh

01:26:00.500 --> 01:26:04.340
[Guest]: Which was supposed to be the better states at that time participated and turned out

01:26:05.220 --> 01:26:07.380
[Guest]: we performed worse than

01:26:08.020 --> 01:26:11.860
[Guest]: Students in Kyrgyzstan and I think after that the government said no we're not going to do this anymore

01:26:12.500 --> 01:26:15.780
[Guest]: As in stop participating now, they're going to restart that participation

01:26:15.860 --> 01:26:20.900
[Guest]: But what that tells me is that we are we if we're going to do education, let's do it

01:26:20.900 --> 01:26:27.460
[Guest]: Well, let's focus on that. Let's focus on fewer things. Let's not focus on everything and that's the problem

01:26:27.460 --> 01:26:32.500
[Guest]: I think and by the way, this is not Modi's creation. I'm not can't blame Modi for this. This has been going on for

01:26:33.700 --> 01:26:35.300
[Guest]: one government after another

01:26:35.300 --> 01:26:38.740
[Guest]: but we now need a situation where we can actually, you know, if

01:26:39.300 --> 01:26:45.220
[Guest]: If we're serious about the country's progress if you're serious about our young people if you're serious about creating opportunities for them

01:26:46.100 --> 01:26:49.000
[Guest]: Then you know, we have to take some tough decisions

01:26:49.540 --> 01:26:53.140
[Amit Varma]: Right. So I I want to move beyond economics and beyond your book right now

01:26:53.140 --> 01:26:59.860
[Amit Varma]: Your book is really about uh, Modi's being a great disappointment or a great betrayal as Raghav would say in terms of economics

01:26:59.860 --> 01:27:05.860
[Amit Varma]: but I want to go beyond that for a moment and ask you about Kashmir because it seems pretty evident to me that

01:27:06.340 --> 01:27:12.340
[Amit Varma]: A lot of things have gone wrong there in the last five years and in fact were going wrong for from even much before that

01:27:12.820 --> 01:27:14.820
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about what's happening

01:27:15.460 --> 01:27:16.660
[Guest]: well

01:27:16.660 --> 01:27:18.660
[Guest]: you know, actually

01:27:18.660 --> 01:27:25.860
[Guest]: During Prime Minister Malishpa's time and then even Dr. Manmohan Singh's time, I think there was a semblance of return to

01:27:26.660 --> 01:27:33.380
[Guest]: Some level of normalcy things had eased off, you know, there's a greater participation in kind of, you know

01:27:35.140 --> 01:27:38.740
[Guest]: Elections and all that just because people felt that thing it was safer

01:27:39.620 --> 01:27:40.580
[Guest]: and

01:27:40.580 --> 01:27:42.900
[Guest]: the rich of the militants had kind of

01:27:43.620 --> 01:27:47.480
[Guest]: You know had subsided. I mean all of their power had subsided

01:27:47.480 --> 01:27:49.480
[Guest]: then in

01:27:50.020 --> 01:27:52.020
[Guest]: 2013-14

01:27:53.080 --> 01:27:59.560
[Guest]: Militancy we started hearing the militancy was beginning to pick up a little bit more. This was in the aftermath of the Abdul Guru hanging

01:28:00.600 --> 01:28:05.080
[Guest]: But it was still very limited. The estimates would be 100 or 200 people and all that stuff and

01:28:06.040 --> 01:28:08.040
[Guest]: That's it killings had come down

01:28:08.760 --> 01:28:10.760
[Guest]: civilian or soldiers

01:28:11.480 --> 01:28:15.880
[Guest]: Fewer people were dying. But I think when the 2014 election came up

01:28:15.880 --> 01:28:19.160
[Guest]: And the verdict was pretty lopsided, you know

01:28:19.720 --> 01:28:23.400
[Guest]: The People's Democratic Party led by Mufti Syed at that time

01:28:23.960 --> 01:28:29.160
[Guest]: Won heavily in Kashmir the BJP won heavily in Jammu. In fact, the Congress did not have a single

01:28:30.120 --> 01:28:33.420
[Guest]: MLA from the Hindu regions of Jammu, which was pretty astonishing

01:28:34.120 --> 01:28:36.280
[Guest]: It was a total kind of polarized verdict

01:28:36.840 --> 01:28:43.080
[Guest]: And of course the government, you know came up and the BJP and the PDP at that time formed the government that created

01:28:43.080 --> 01:28:49.480
[Guest]: I think a lot of disquiet in Kashmir and it was almost like oh now the BJP is going to rule us

01:28:49.800 --> 01:28:54.920
[Guest]: The same BJP that the PDP had vilified and fought against during the assembly election

01:28:55.480 --> 01:28:59.720
[Guest]: So I think the space for political discourse actually shrank

01:29:00.280 --> 01:29:05.640
[Guest]: So again, there was polarization in that sense that militancy started creeping up and

01:29:06.440 --> 01:29:10.760
[Guest]: If you remember in the last four or five years a rhetoric on television

01:29:10.760 --> 01:29:13.960
[Guest]: And obviously political rhetoric has been pretty much about

01:29:14.520 --> 01:29:18.040
[Guest]: Kashmiris as terrorists, Kashmiris as terrorist lovers, this thing, that thing

01:29:18.360 --> 01:29:22.600
[Guest]: I think it was this vilification campaign that kind of put Kashmiris in a corner

01:29:22.600 --> 01:29:28.200
[Guest]: So in some ways it was like I'm not surprised that there's so much anger and resentment in Kashmir now

01:29:28.840 --> 01:29:30.840
[Guest]: There's more violence now

01:29:31.400 --> 01:29:37.640
[Guest]: And because I think Kashmir suits BJP's politics greatly personally. This is what I think, you know

01:29:37.640 --> 01:29:42.120
[Guest]: The Congress party has always had this philosophy that in J&K

01:29:42.120 --> 01:29:48.520
[Guest]: The Congress party should not try to kind of bring in its central dominating kind of politics

01:29:48.520 --> 01:29:53.480
[Guest]: Because regional parties are better able to kind of deal with regional aspirations

01:29:53.480 --> 01:29:56.120
[Guest]: And it's a very, I think it's a very deliberate kind of thing

01:29:56.120 --> 01:30:03.240
[Guest]: As far as the BJP is concerned, the BJP views Kashmir as a lever for national politics

01:30:03.240 --> 01:30:07.720
[Guest]: It's the exact opposite of how the Congress sees J&K

01:30:07.720 --> 01:30:14.600
[Guest]: So I'm not at all surprised by how things have deteriorated in Kashmir

01:30:14.600 --> 01:30:19.400
[Guest]: And they have, you know, more people. I mean, I think everybody's kind of seen the numbers now

01:30:19.400 --> 01:30:25.800
[Guest]: More soldiers died in 2018 than in any year since 2008

01:30:26.680 --> 01:30:29.640
[Guest]: So more civilians dying

01:30:29.640 --> 01:30:34.760
[Guest]: There's no end to this conflict, you know, and it's been going on for 30 years

01:30:34.760 --> 01:30:39.480
[Guest]: I think the best hope was when Prime Minister Vajpayee was in control

01:30:39.480 --> 01:30:45.320
[Guest]: And then also to some extent where the Musharraf was bouncing, you know, that formula

01:30:45.320 --> 01:30:51.080
[Guest]: But then everything since then has kind of, you know, petered out, things have gotten worse

01:30:51.080 --> 01:30:56.520
[Guest]: And so I don't know. I mean, I think BJP has to be very careful

01:30:56.520 --> 01:31:00.280
[Guest]: In not making everything political

01:31:00.280 --> 01:31:06.680
[Guest]: National interests cannot be, you know, in some ways I feel that BJP doesn't think of

01:31:06.680 --> 01:31:11.880
[Guest]: It places the party political interest above the national interest as far as Kashmir is concerned

01:31:11.880 --> 01:31:17.400
[Guest]: And by the way, for that, I think it may be that BJP does not view the national interest

01:31:17.400 --> 01:31:21.960
[Guest]: The same way the rest of us do, because maybe they think that the state of the nation right now

01:31:21.960 --> 01:31:23.960
[Guest]: This is not the nation that we want to be

01:31:23.960 --> 01:31:28.920
[Guest]: They want a different type of nation. So, you know, if you don't think that this is the kind of nation you wanted

01:31:28.920 --> 01:31:33.400
[Guest]: Then you can place political interest above what we consider the national interest

01:31:33.400 --> 01:31:37.240
[Guest]: Because you're trying to get to a different nation state and different national interest

01:31:37.240 --> 01:31:40.040
[Guest]: So in that sense, it makes sense from their political perspective

01:31:40.040 --> 01:31:45.320
[Guest]: It makes sense. Maybe they want a different India and Kashmir suits that purpose

01:31:45.320 --> 01:31:49.400
[Guest]: And also in the popular rhetoric these days party is equal to nation in their rhetoric

01:31:49.400 --> 01:31:54.360
[Amit Varma]: So if you're anti-BJP, you're automatically considered anti-national

01:31:54.360 --> 01:31:59.800
[Amit Varma]: So Salman, now that I've got you on the show, I also have to ask you questions about the Congress

01:31:59.800 --> 01:32:03.880
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is for a democracy to be healthy, you need a healthy opposition

01:32:03.880 --> 01:32:09.880
[Amit Varma]: And the decline of the Congress is something that has, you know, I mean, I used to write against the Congress all the time

01:32:09.880 --> 01:32:14.360
[Amit Varma]: When they were in power and now, of course, I write against the BJP all the time because they're in power

01:32:14.360 --> 01:32:18.840
[Amit Varma]: But one of the things that has happened is in 2016, you know, the Congress has been in power

01:32:18.840 --> 01:32:25.640
[Amit Varma]: And in 2014, Congress declined massively to 44 seats and the health of the party is something that is called in concern

01:32:25.640 --> 01:32:31.560
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that dismays many of us about it is that unlike the BJP

01:32:31.560 --> 01:32:37.800
[Amit Varma]: That doesn't really seem to be an active grassroots and a cadre from which leaders spontaneously emerge

01:32:37.800 --> 01:32:41.480
[Amit Varma]: What you instead have is a continuation of a series of dynasties

01:32:41.480 --> 01:32:47.720
[Amit Varma]: Like I look across the party today, even apart from Rahul Gandhi, you have Shindia and Pilate

01:32:47.720 --> 01:32:53.720
[Amit Varma]: And if I may say so, even yourself, you know, who are part of dynasties

01:32:53.720 --> 01:32:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, Rahul Gandhi himself used to talk about inner party democracy once upon a time

01:32:59.000 --> 01:33:03.880
[Amit Varma]: But we don't see that and even if it was there, where are the cadres? Where are the grassroots?

01:33:03.880 --> 01:33:09.560
[Guest]: Okay, so these are actually two different questions because first, let's talk about the dynasty part

01:33:09.560 --> 01:33:14.440
[Guest]: And you're right, my father, like I said earlier, has been a politician for a long time

01:33:14.440 --> 01:33:21.240
[Guest]: And to be totally transparent, of course, when I joined politics, you know, I got immediate recognition

01:33:21.240 --> 01:33:25.320
[Guest]: Because of my father, right? Because they knew who he was

01:33:25.320 --> 01:33:29.160
[Guest]: Now in politics, you know, you really have to prove yourself

01:33:29.160 --> 01:33:34.440
[Guest]: And ultimately, people will, you may make it to a certain point and say, okay, you know

01:33:34.440 --> 01:33:37.080
[Guest]: I'm going to compete for this particular seat or whatever

01:33:37.080 --> 01:33:41.400
[Guest]: But ultimately, it's the people who decide whether you're the right person for them or not

01:33:41.400 --> 01:33:46.120
[Guest]: So I think in that sense, this dynasty part is not specific to Congress

01:33:46.120 --> 01:33:49.720
[Guest]: I mean, of course, you see similar things in other political parties as well

01:33:49.720 --> 01:33:51.560
[Guest]: And in other countries as well

01:33:51.560 --> 01:33:58.920
[Guest]: What matters is whether or not whoever is in politics, at least to my mind, are they delivering for the people?

01:33:58.920 --> 01:34:03.400
[Guest]: If they're not, they'll be, you know, you can't really, you can't keep them

01:34:04.040 --> 01:34:08.440
[Guest]: As in, you know, people, it is up to the people ultimately to whether or not they keep them or not

01:34:08.440 --> 01:34:11.480
[Guest]: Of course, and by the way, this isn't going to go away

01:34:11.480 --> 01:34:13.640
[Guest]: Just because we may feel a certain way about it

01:34:14.200 --> 01:34:20.840
[Guest]: Because it's, you know, this has been happening historically

01:34:20.840 --> 01:34:23.880
[Guest]: It's going to continue happening in India and elsewhere

01:34:23.880 --> 01:34:26.040
[Guest]: So that's the one part about dynasty

01:34:26.040 --> 01:34:33.640
[Guest]: Yes, do we have other leaders who are coming in who are not related to politicians?

01:34:33.640 --> 01:34:37.880
[Guest]: Of course, I mean, I'm sure that, you know, we tend to focus on dynasties

01:34:37.880 --> 01:34:39.880
[Guest]: Because they're easy to kind of comprehend

01:34:39.880 --> 01:34:41.560
[Guest]: They're easy to calculate

01:34:41.560 --> 01:34:45.000
[Guest]: But there's so many people that I know of in our party, in other parties

01:34:45.000 --> 01:34:46.040
[Guest]: Who have nothing to do with politics

01:34:46.040 --> 01:34:49.960
[Guest]: They're first-time politicians and they're doing extremely well

01:34:49.960 --> 01:34:55.320
[Guest]: So on the dynasty part, frankly, I don't really see it as something that is inherently bad

01:34:55.880 --> 01:35:01.160
[Guest]: Unless you feel that dynasties can be sustained without people's support

01:35:01.160 --> 01:35:04.840
[Guest]: Ultimately, people will have to weigh in in a democracy

01:35:04.840 --> 01:35:07.880
[Guest]: And when they do, sometimes you win, sometimes you lose

01:35:07.880 --> 01:35:09.080
[Guest]: Depends on how well you've done

01:35:09.080 --> 01:35:10.600
[Guest]: I lost an election myself

01:35:10.600 --> 01:35:14.200
[Guest]: My first election, I lost myself despite the fact that, you know

01:35:14.200 --> 01:35:15.560
[Guest]: I felt that I was a good candidate

01:35:15.560 --> 01:35:16.760
[Guest]: I'd gone to the World Bank

01:35:16.760 --> 01:35:18.040
[Guest]: I had a lot of policy experience

01:35:18.840 --> 01:35:21.720
[Guest]: Had no scandals per se

01:35:21.720 --> 01:35:22.680
[Guest]: I was well-meaning

01:35:23.240 --> 01:35:24.840
[Guest]: But, you know, people saw it different

01:35:24.840 --> 01:35:27.880
[Guest]: People felt that a different candidate was better for them

01:35:27.880 --> 01:35:31.480
[Guest]: Because maybe he came from their part of the world or whatever

01:35:31.480 --> 01:35:34.920
[Guest]: So democracy has that equalizing effect, I think

01:35:35.720 --> 01:35:39.720
[Guest]: As far as the carders and where are the carders, what's happening

01:35:39.720 --> 01:35:41.800
[Guest]: Why isn't the Congress, you know, people say

01:35:41.800 --> 01:35:43.000
[Guest]: The RSS is everywhere

01:35:43.000 --> 01:35:44.360
[Guest]: Where is the Congress party?

01:35:44.360 --> 01:35:49.080
[Guest]: You know, there is this thing about, to my mind, about liberal politics everywhere

01:35:49.720 --> 01:35:53.880
[Guest]: That it seems that when it comes to being on the ground

01:35:53.880 --> 01:36:00.600
[Guest]: They seem to be less kind of active than, say, people who are on the far right

01:36:01.160 --> 01:36:02.520
[Guest]: I don't know why that is the case

01:36:02.520 --> 01:36:06.760
[Guest]: I mean, I hear about similar complaints in the US, in Europe

01:36:07.080 --> 01:36:10.840
[Guest]: That is, you know, the carder-based political parties

01:36:11.480 --> 01:36:12.840
[Guest]: Which are typically left of center

01:36:12.840 --> 01:36:15.880
[Guest]: They don't seem to be as active as the far right

01:36:15.880 --> 01:36:17.960
[Guest]: Now, it has been my experience

01:36:17.960 --> 01:36:23.720
[Guest]: That even if you don't see the kind of same visible RSS ground game

01:36:23.720 --> 01:36:29.560
[Guest]: I've seen in my own experience, Congress supporters are in the unlikeliest of places

01:36:29.560 --> 01:36:32.280
[Guest]: In Kashmir, I can't tell you, there are these

01:36:32.280 --> 01:36:35.240
[Guest]: I bet so many people who support Congress

01:36:35.240 --> 01:36:38.440
[Guest]: And for no, I mean, and it kind of really puzzled me

01:36:38.440 --> 01:36:42.920
[Guest]: I was like, you guys never, you know, PDP and NC always win here

01:36:42.920 --> 01:36:45.320
[Guest]: How are you still with the Congress?

01:36:45.320 --> 01:36:46.520
[Guest]: Very different reasons

01:36:46.520 --> 01:36:48.040
[Guest]: But they're still there

01:36:48.040 --> 01:36:53.880
[Guest]: So I think in this particular election, we're going to see a different kind of outcome, I think

01:36:53.880 --> 01:36:57.400
[Guest]: And that outcome is not possible if you don't have feet on the ground

01:36:57.400 --> 01:37:00.360
[Guest]: But we need to pay a lot more attention to this

01:37:00.360 --> 01:37:03.000
[Guest]: I think now, politics is changing

01:37:03.000 --> 01:37:06.520
[Guest]: The threat from the far right is far too significant

01:37:06.520 --> 01:37:10.680
[Guest]: It cannot be kind of, it cannot be disregarded

01:37:10.680 --> 01:37:14.920
[Guest]: I think time has come for political parties to be more active

01:37:14.920 --> 01:37:19.160
[Guest]: Political parties like the Congress to pay a lot more attention to organization

01:37:19.160 --> 01:37:22.680
[Guest]: And mobilizing resources

01:37:22.680 --> 01:37:26.920
[Guest]: But, you know, we are in a difficult situation right now

01:37:26.920 --> 01:37:28.520
[Guest]: Because we have limited resources

01:37:28.520 --> 01:37:30.200
[Guest]: And we are fighting this election

01:37:30.200 --> 01:37:31.640
[Guest]: And it's not that easy

01:37:31.640 --> 01:37:33.800
[Guest]: But let's see what the outcome is

01:37:33.800 --> 01:37:37.160
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, if I may speculate, I mean, on the one hand, it's

01:37:37.160 --> 01:37:41.800
[Amit Varma]: If I may say so, the Congress in recent years has seemed to be a party

01:37:41.800 --> 01:37:44.440
[Amit Varma]: Which just wants to come to power, doesn't really believe in anything

01:37:44.440 --> 01:37:47.960
[Amit Varma]: What are really the core beliefs, if I may take a skeptic's view

01:37:47.960 --> 01:37:52.360
[Amit Varma]: But if I, you know, on the other hand, to be a two-handed economist

01:37:53.080 --> 01:37:56.120
[Amit Varma]: If I, you know, one reason if I may speculate

01:37:56.120 --> 01:38:00.200
[Amit Varma]: Why liberal parties have less of an impact at the grassroots

01:38:00.200 --> 01:38:05.800
[Amit Varma]: And far right parties do is that because hate is a bigger motivating factor than hope is

01:38:05.800 --> 01:38:07.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, hope can become very diffused

01:38:07.880 --> 01:38:11.320
[Amit Varma]: And there is a free rider effect and all of those things

01:38:11.320 --> 01:38:16.360
[Amit Varma]: Whereas, you know, the more you whip up hate, the better the turnout you're going to get

01:38:16.360 --> 01:38:19.800
[Amit Varma]: Which is, you know, really worrying

01:38:19.800 --> 01:38:21.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, I have another question

01:38:21.640 --> 01:38:23.560
[Amit Varma]: You guys just released your manifesto

01:38:23.560 --> 01:38:27.640
[Amit Varma]: And my other question sort of goes back to the BJP manifesto of 2014

01:38:27.640 --> 01:38:28.680
[Amit Varma]: And I'll quote from your book

01:38:29.640 --> 01:38:33.320
[Amit Varma]: Quote, the manifesto accused the UPA of not maintaining that growth

01:38:33.320 --> 01:38:36.040
[Amit Varma]: And leaving the next government with sub 5% growth

01:38:36.040 --> 01:38:40.520
[Amit Varma]: The BJP charged that the UPA pushed the country backwards by 20 years

01:38:40.520 --> 01:38:42.760
[Amit Varma]: And that millions of men and women were jobless

01:38:42.760 --> 01:38:44.680
[Amit Varma]: Arguing that the country had lost hope

01:38:44.680 --> 01:38:47.880
[Amit Varma]: The BJP cast itself as a party that would act decisively

01:38:47.880 --> 01:38:51.000
[Amit Varma]: To address the country's challenges on a priority basis

01:38:51.000 --> 01:38:51.720
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote

01:38:51.720 --> 01:38:55.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, what strikes me is that one, obviously, that their manifesto

01:38:55.240 --> 01:38:59.000
[Amit Varma]: Had a lot of things in it which were good as you yourself said

01:38:59.000 --> 01:39:00.520
[Amit Varma]: But the other thing is that this could

01:39:00.520 --> 01:39:03.640
[Amit Varma]: This exact sentence could be used for today

01:39:03.640 --> 01:39:05.720
[Amit Varma]: Just changing the UPA and the BJP

01:39:05.720 --> 01:39:07.000
[Amit Varma]: Just switching them

01:39:07.000 --> 01:39:11.400
[Amit Varma]: Where you have the Congress talking about how the BJP has done such a miserable job

01:39:11.400 --> 01:39:13.960
[Amit Varma]: Over the last few years, which is absolutely true

01:39:13.960 --> 01:39:16.440
[Amit Varma]: And equally promising drastic action

01:39:16.440 --> 01:39:20.680
[Amit Varma]: Now, my question is, why should anyone take manifesto seriously?

01:39:20.680 --> 01:39:25.080
[Amit Varma]: Because as we've seen, the BJP did not follow up on their manifesto of 2014

01:39:25.080 --> 01:39:29.400
[Amit Varma]: And you know, if I can ask a specific question that struck me from your manifesto

01:39:29.400 --> 01:39:31.720
[Amit Varma]: Like, there's lots in your manifesto to like

01:39:31.720 --> 01:39:34.760
[Amit Varma]: For example, one of the promises you guys make is that

01:39:34.760 --> 01:39:39.480
[Amit Varma]: Cities will be empowered and, you know, empowered mayors will be elected

01:39:39.480 --> 01:39:41.400
[Amit Varma]: And therefore governance will be better

01:39:41.400 --> 01:39:43.560
[Amit Varma]: But the question that struck me when I saw this was that

01:39:43.560 --> 01:39:45.480
[Amit Varma]: Wait a minute, this is a state subject

01:39:45.480 --> 01:39:48.920
[Amit Varma]: This is, you know, the national government has nothing to do with this at all

01:39:48.920 --> 01:39:51.800
[Amit Varma]: The Congress is already in a power in a number of states

01:39:51.800 --> 01:39:54.200
[Amit Varma]: And they could do this now if they wanted to

01:39:54.200 --> 01:39:57.160
[Amit Varma]: So what is it in this manifesto for? Is it just posturing?

01:39:57.720 --> 01:40:00.680
[Guest]: Well, I think it's not posturing per se

01:40:00.680 --> 01:40:03.800
[Guest]: I think it is in some ways trying to draw a philosophical line

01:40:03.800 --> 01:40:08.760
[Guest]: Because decentralization, like the one you talked about in terms of urban governance reforms

01:40:08.760 --> 01:40:11.880
[Guest]: First, you know, urban governance reforms are needed, necessary

01:40:11.880 --> 01:40:13.400
[Guest]: Without that, you can't really do much

01:40:13.400 --> 01:40:17.320
[Guest]: At least you have to have a statement which says, look, this is important

01:40:17.320 --> 01:40:22.440
[Guest]: And it is important, especially if India continues to urbanize

01:40:22.440 --> 01:40:27.320
[Guest]: And by the way, I don't really believe the figure that India is 70% or 69% rural right now

01:40:27.320 --> 01:40:30.520
[Guest]: I think a lot of what has happened is that the landscape has transformed

01:40:30.520 --> 01:40:35.800
[Guest]: Cities and villages are getting fused together through other settlements

01:40:37.000 --> 01:40:41.080
[Guest]: So I think India may be a bit more urbanized than we think it is

01:40:41.080 --> 01:40:43.320
[Guest]: And for that, we need new governance systems

01:40:43.320 --> 01:40:44.680
[Guest]: We do need decentralization

01:40:44.680 --> 01:40:48.440
[Guest]: And in some ways, this is part of the Congress Party's core philosophy

01:40:48.440 --> 01:40:51.480
[Guest]: Going back to the 73rd and 74th Amendment

01:40:51.480 --> 01:40:57.000
[Guest]: Going back to what Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi had wanted to do through Panchayat Raj and all that

01:40:57.000 --> 01:41:00.600
[Guest]: So I think the aspiration remains

01:41:00.600 --> 01:41:02.520
[Guest]: I think the philosophical statement remains

01:41:02.520 --> 01:41:09.160
[Guest]: I think what we have to do a far better job of is to actually implement the thing, right?

01:41:10.120 --> 01:41:15.560
[Guest]: To persuade governments at the state levels to say, look, we have to do this

01:41:15.560 --> 01:41:20.920
[Guest]: It is, you know, in some ways, you can't really dictate to state governments these days, obviously

01:41:20.920 --> 01:41:24.520
[Guest]: I mean, unless you're a BJP and you control more than half the country

01:41:24.520 --> 01:41:25.560
[Guest]: And maybe you can

01:41:25.560 --> 01:41:27.160
[Guest]: And that would have made it easier

01:41:27.160 --> 01:41:29.160
[Guest]: But, you know, in some ways, you have to persuade governments

01:41:29.160 --> 01:41:32.920
[Guest]: And you had to kind of create models in other states and say, look, I mean, this is working really well here

01:41:32.920 --> 01:41:34.840
[Guest]: People are benefiting here

01:41:34.840 --> 01:41:36.760
[Guest]: Other states should follow suit

01:41:36.760 --> 01:41:41.400
[Guest]: But it is not, you know, I do think that manifestos are serious documents

01:41:41.400 --> 01:41:45.640
[Guest]: If you look at the BJP's manifesto, also, they try to follow up on a lot of different things

01:41:45.640 --> 01:41:51.960
[Guest]: But I think what, you know, like electrification and this thing and that thing

01:41:51.960 --> 01:41:57.880
[Guest]: But I think what BJP missed out on was the broader kind of policy reforms

01:41:57.880 --> 01:42:03.320
[Guest]: So, in fact, if you look at all the promises, there's so many that they actually did try to follow up on

01:42:03.320 --> 01:42:07.160
[Guest]: Whether that was the right thing or not, that's different

01:42:07.160 --> 01:42:09.240
[Guest]: But they tried to follow up on a lot of things

01:42:09.240 --> 01:42:14.200
[Guest]: The Congress Party, too, will, you know, this is one way to hold political parties accountable

01:42:15.160 --> 01:42:21.000
[Guest]: But I do think that this particular Congress manifesto has some very important

01:42:21.000 --> 01:42:24.040
[Guest]: Statements and that have to do with the role of the state

01:42:24.040 --> 01:42:28.040
[Guest]: To my mind, I have not come across any Congress manifesto which actually says

01:42:28.040 --> 01:42:31.880
[Guest]: That the private sector will lead through investment

01:42:31.880 --> 01:42:35.000
[Guest]: And the public sector will focus on public goods

01:42:35.000 --> 01:42:37.480
[Guest]: Or, you know, for the most part

01:42:37.480 --> 01:42:41.480
[Guest]: I mean, that's a pretty interesting statement to make, right?

01:42:41.480 --> 01:42:43.560
[Guest]: I mean, this is what people like me like

01:42:43.560 --> 01:42:47.560
[Guest]: I'm sure, Amit, you also want something similar where the private sector is

01:42:47.560 --> 01:42:51.160
[Guest]: At least in a statement, unleashed

01:42:51.160 --> 01:42:55.880
[Guest]: And then the public sector is redefined for public goods

01:42:55.880 --> 01:42:58.600
[Guest]: So, I think very important, very important

01:42:58.600 --> 01:43:03.800
[Guest]: Also, our commitment to individual freedoms in this manifesto

01:43:03.800 --> 01:43:05.880
[Guest]: I think that is very important

01:43:05.880 --> 01:43:09.880
[Guest]: And I think part of it may be born out of our experience with the current government

01:43:09.880 --> 01:43:16.840
[Guest]: And how this government has actually threatened a lot of our personal freedoms

01:43:16.840 --> 01:43:22.360
[Guest]: So, maybe the next government that we hopefully have something to do with

01:43:22.360 --> 01:43:26.360
[Guest]: Will kind of implement an agenda where we can strengthen these freedoms

01:43:26.360 --> 01:43:28.680
[Guest]: So that whichever government comes in the future

01:43:29.640 --> 01:43:33.320
[Guest]: At least will face the pressure from citizenry as well as institutions alike

01:43:33.880 --> 01:43:36.600
[Guest]: So, I know there's a lot of cynicism

01:43:36.600 --> 01:43:38.920
[Guest]: I know it's not misplaced

01:43:38.920 --> 01:43:41.800
[Guest]: But at the same time, you know, we have to have some hope

01:43:41.800 --> 01:43:44.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I've been writing from say the early 2000s

01:43:44.760 --> 01:43:46.920
[Amit Varma]: About our free speech laws

01:43:46.920 --> 01:43:49.160
[Amit Varma]: Not just the sedition law, which you guys have said you will abolish

01:43:49.160 --> 01:43:52.760
[Amit Varma]: But also 295A, 153A, things you haven't mentioned

01:43:52.760 --> 01:43:56.760
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, the Congress after all was the party that banned the Satanic verses

01:43:56.760 --> 01:43:57.880
[Amit Varma]: Which remains banned

01:43:57.880 --> 01:44:02.440
[Amit Varma]: But I completely buy your point that it's important to change the rhetoric

01:44:02.440 --> 01:44:07.800
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, that the commitment that you guys have explicitly made to individual rights

01:44:07.800 --> 01:44:11.480
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, the primacy of the private sector is great

01:44:11.480 --> 01:44:14.040
[Amit Varma]: Let's see how much of that really happens

01:44:14.040 --> 01:44:15.160
[Amit Varma]: I'll kind of...

01:44:15.160 --> 01:44:18.120
[Amit Varma]: And regarding what you said about urban development

01:44:18.120 --> 01:44:19.320
[Amit Varma]: Obviously, I agree with you

01:44:19.320 --> 01:44:21.240
[Amit Varma]: I had an episode a few weeks back

01:44:21.240 --> 01:44:24.280
[Amit Varma]: Which I'll link from the episode page with Ruben Abraham and Pritika Hingorani

01:44:24.280 --> 01:44:25.720
[Amit Varma]: Of the IDFC Institute

01:44:25.720 --> 01:44:29.560
[Amit Varma]: On how India is far more urban than we think

01:44:29.560 --> 01:44:33.240
[Amit Varma]: And what we should do to smooth that process

01:44:33.240 --> 01:44:35.400
[Amit Varma]: You know, I've taken a lot of your time

01:44:35.400 --> 01:44:39.240
[Amit Varma]: Sort of a final question to end with

01:44:39.240 --> 01:44:45.480
[Amit Varma]: Which is, again, I ask you to answer this not wearing your hat as a Congress spokesperson

01:44:45.480 --> 01:44:47.720
[Amit Varma]: But as wearing your hat as an Indian citizen

01:44:47.720 --> 01:44:51.880
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, much of the book is written with that hat, frankly, as I was surprised by

01:44:51.880 --> 01:44:54.200
[Amit Varma]: But just wearing the hat of an Indian citizen

01:44:54.200 --> 01:44:57.320
[Amit Varma]: If you look forward to, say, the next five years

01:44:57.320 --> 01:44:59.800
[Amit Varma]: What gives you hope and what gives you despair?

01:44:59.800 --> 01:45:07.800
[Guest]: Well, what gives me hope is that, frankly, we really need to change the rhetoric

01:45:07.800 --> 01:45:12.760
[Guest]: Frankly, we've reached a bit of a crisis point as far as the economy is concerned

01:45:12.760 --> 01:45:17.640
[Guest]: I think the inequality, the rising inequality

01:45:17.640 --> 01:45:21.320
[Guest]: And the kind of lack of good, decent job creation

01:45:21.320 --> 01:45:25.080
[Guest]: Along with this demographic kind of imperative

01:45:25.080 --> 01:45:29.160
[Guest]: I think is creating a situation where we have no choice but to act

01:45:29.160 --> 01:45:31.880
[Guest]: So remember how sometimes we act because there's a crisis

01:45:31.880 --> 01:45:34.200
[Guest]: I think the crisis point is reached

01:45:35.240 --> 01:45:36.760
[Guest]: And I think we have to do something

01:45:36.760 --> 01:45:40.200
[Guest]: I mean, no matter what government comes, I think we have to do something drastic

01:45:40.200 --> 01:45:41.240
[Guest]: Otherwise, we're in trouble

01:45:41.240 --> 01:45:42.520
[Guest]: I think India is in trouble otherwise

01:45:42.520 --> 01:45:43.400
[Guest]: So I think I'm hoping

01:45:44.200 --> 01:45:52.040
[Guest]: The hope is that policymakers understand and realize that there is a serious situation in India

01:45:52.040 --> 01:45:53.800
[Guest]: Especially on the employment front

01:45:53.800 --> 01:45:56.120
[Guest]: And by the way, that is direct linkages to inequality

01:45:56.120 --> 01:45:59.000
[Guest]: And that something has to be done

01:45:59.800 --> 01:46:01.800
[Guest]: And so that gives me hope

01:46:01.800 --> 01:46:04.360
[Guest]: Of course, what causes me concern is that

01:46:04.360 --> 01:46:07.080
[Guest]: Policymakers may not get it

01:46:07.080 --> 01:46:12.280
[Guest]: And like has happened in this government's term

01:46:12.280 --> 01:46:16.520
[Guest]: That they may actually end up doing more harm than good

01:46:16.520 --> 01:46:17.880
[Guest]: In fact, one of the principles

01:46:17.880 --> 01:46:22.280
[Guest]: I actually talked about four principles of policymaking

01:46:23.080 --> 01:46:25.720
[Guest]: And one of them is, you know, do no harm

01:46:26.520 --> 01:46:29.640
[Guest]: I never thought I would have to write something like that

01:46:29.640 --> 01:46:31.960
[Guest]: Do no harm as a principle of policymaking

01:46:31.960 --> 01:46:35.480
[Guest]: But I think, you know, after the experience of this government

01:46:35.480 --> 01:46:39.000
[Guest]: I'm, you know, I think it's sensible to include something like that

01:46:39.000 --> 01:46:46.680
[Guest]: So yeah, so hope and caution are both linked to this moment in our history

01:46:46.680 --> 01:46:50.040
[Guest]: And there are clear dangers ahead

01:46:50.040 --> 01:46:51.080
[Guest]: There's a crisis

01:46:51.080 --> 01:46:53.320
[Guest]: In my view, there's a crisis in the country

01:46:53.320 --> 01:46:55.640
[Guest]: And it's only going to get worse, by the way

01:46:55.640 --> 01:46:57.560
[Guest]: It's not going to improve if we don't do something

01:46:57.560 --> 01:46:59.800
[Guest]: And that gives me hope that we may end up doing something

01:46:59.800 --> 01:47:03.240
[Guest]: Because when it's this crisis time, when it's crunch time

01:47:03.240 --> 01:47:06.040
[Guest]: Some of us step forward and do something about it

01:47:06.040 --> 01:47:07.960
[Guest]: And that's what I hope from the next government

